Xing¬†Ju¬†Lee School of Mathematical Sciences, Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia ARC Centre of Excellence in Mathematical and Statistical Frontiers (ACEMS), Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia Centre of Research Excellence in Reducing Healthcare Associated Infections (CRE-RHAI), Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia Markus¬†Hainy 222e-mail: markus.hainy@jku.at School of Mathematical Sciences, Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia Department of Applied Statistics, Johannes Kepler University, Linz, Austria James¬†P.¬†McKeone School of Mathematical Sciences, Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia Christopher¬†C.¬†Drovandi School of Mathematical Sciences, Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia ARC Centre of Excellence in Mathematical and Statistical Frontiers (ACEMS), Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia Anthony¬†N.¬†Pettitt School of Mathematical Sciences, Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia ARC Centre of Excellence in Mathematical and Statistical Frontiers (ACEMS), Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, Australia
Abstract

Max-stable processes are a common choice for modelling spatial extreme data as they arise naturally as the infinite-dimensional generalisation of multivariate extreme value theory. Statistical inference for such models is complicated by the intractability of the multivariate density function. Nonparametric, composite likelihood-based, and Bayesian approaches have been proposed to address this difficulty. More recently, a simulation-based approach using approximate Bayesian computation (ABC) has been employed for estimating parameters of max-stable models. ABC algorithms rely on the evaluation of discrepancies between model simulations and the observed data rather than explicit evaluations of computationally expensive or intractable likelihood functions. The use of an ABC method to perform model selection for max-stable models is explored. Three max-stable models are regarded: the extremal-tùë°t model with either a Whittle-Mat√©rn or a powered exponential covariance function, and the Brown-Resnick model with power variogram. In addition, the non-extremal Student-tùë°t copula model with a Whittle-Mat√©rn or a powered exponential covariance function is also considered. The method is applied to annual maximum temperature data from 25 weather stations dispersed around South Australia.

Keywords: Approximate Bayesian computation; Max-stable models; Copula models; Maximum temperature data; Model selection

1 Introduction

The statistical analysis of extreme data offers a unique challenge as the interest lies in the tails of the distribution and is of importance in a wide range of application fields, e.g., finance (Embrechts et¬†al., 1997), hydrology (Katz et¬†al., 2002) and engineering and meteorology (Castillo et¬†al., 2004). Special consideration was given to develop statistical models particular for univariate extreme data, which have now been generalised into a family of distributions known as the generalised extreme value (GEV) distribution with three subfamilies (Fr√©chet, Gumbel and Weibull) following the Fisher-Tippett-Gnedenko theorem. Coles (2001) provides an excellent introductory treatment of the topic. A particular feature of the GEV distribution is its max-stable property. The max-stable property implies that the maximum of independent copies of a random variable is distributionally invariant up to location and scaling parameters.

Extensions of max-stable models to multivariate extreme data have been limited initially by the intractability of the model likelihood except for some low-dimensional cases. These special cases are of limited use in most applications, where typical multivariate extreme applications arise from spatial data with a large number of spatial locations. Even current approaches to parameter estimation for spatial extremes models avoid the computation of the likelihood, relying instead on nonparametric (de¬†Haan and Pereira, 2006), composite likelihood (Padoan et¬†al., 2010), or simulated maximum likelihood (Koch, 2014) methods. For threshold exceedance models, full likelihood-based inference has been proposed by Wadsworth and Tawn (2014) and Engelke et¬†al. (2015) for the Brown-Resnick model and Thibaud and Opitz (2015) for the extremal-tùë°t model. Stephenson and Tawn (2005) show that the likelihood function simplifies substantially if it is known for which locations the extremal events are occurring at the same time so that the locations can be partitioned accordingly. Regarding these partitions as latent variables, Dombry et¬†al. (2017b) construct a stochastic Expectation-Maximisation (EM) algorithm for exact maximum likelihood estimation of the parameters of multivariate max-stable models. Similarly, Thibaud et¬†al. (2016) develop a Gibbs sampler by conditioning on these partitions to conduct Bayesian inference for a Brown-Resnick process. However, these conditional likelihoods are still rather expensive to evaluate as they contain multivariate normal (Brown-Resnick model) or multivariate Student-tùë°t (extremal-tùë°t model) cumulative distribution functions. Dombry et¬†al. (2017a) extend the idea of Thibaud et¬†al. (2016) to several other models and prove the asymptotic normality and efficiency of the posterior median for these models, among them the extremal-tùë°t and the Brown-Resnick model. Former attempts to perform Bayesian inference for max-stable models include Ribatet et¬†al. (2012). They replace the true likelihood with the misspecified composite likelihood, which results in overly precise posterior distributions so that adjustments need to be applied.

To avoid the evaluation of the likelihood for Bayesian inference, approximate Bayesian computation (ABC) (Erhardt and Smith, 2012) methods have been proposed to estimate model parameters. ABC methods rely on simulations from the max-stable models rather than evaluations of the (approximate) model likelihood in order to perform the required statistical inference. Only model simulations which are ‚Äòsimilar‚Äô to the observed data are used in the inference, where the measure of similarity is typically a function of informative summary statistics.

There are not many instances where ABC has been applied in the context of extremes. Erhardt and Sisson (2015) provide an introduction to the use of ABC methods in modelling extremes. The first application of ABC methods in an extremes context is Bortot et¬†al. (2007), where an MCMC ABC algorithm is used for stereological extremes. Subsequent ABC work has focused on spatial extremes (Erhardt and Smith, 2012; Barthelm√© et¬†al., 2015; Prangle, 2016; Ruli et¬†al., 2016; Hainy et¬†al., 2016). Barthelm√© et¬†al. (2015), Prangle (2016) and Ruli et¬†al. (2016) use spatial extremes examples to illustrate the performance of their proposed ABC methods for parameter estimation, where the common goal is to alleviate the high computational burden that ABC methods for spatial extremes entail. A different perspective of using ABC methods for spatial extremes applications is provided by Hainy et¬†al. (2016), where the optimal design for estimating the spatial dependence structure of extremes is sought.

None of the previous work mentioned investigates model selection for spatial extremes applications using ABC. This is the focus of our paper. The aim is to use ABC to determine the posterior model probabilities for models that describe the spatial dependence of the annual maximum temperature data collected from weather stations located around the state of South Australia. These posterior probabilities can be used to select the most preferred model or to perform Bayesian model averaging. An accurate representation of the generating process of the spatial maxima would also allow for a more accurate depiction of the spatial distribution of the maximum temperature across the region. This is useful in estimating the maxima at locations with no observations. For our application, we will consider two extremal-tùë°t models (Opitz, 2013) with different correlation functions and the Brown-Resnick model (Brown and Resnick, 1977; Kabluchko et¬†al., 2009). By way of contrast, we will also include two non-extremal Student-tùë°t copula models (Demarta and McNeil, 2005) with different correlation functions to our set of possible models.

To facilitate the task of selecting informative summary statistics, we employ the ‚Äòsemi-automatic‚Äô summary selection schemes of Fearnhead and Prangle (2012) for parameter estimation and Prangle et¬†al. (2014) for model selection, see also Lee et¬†al. (2015). The summary statistics we consider for this purpose are listed in Sections¬†2.3 and 2.4. Moreover, the method of Prangle et¬†al. (2014) aims to construct summary statistics for model choice which are close to being Bayes sufficient. This is important because ABC for model choice can lead to inaccurate results if the summary statistics are not sufficient (Robert et¬†al., 2011).

For the actual ABC algorithm, we follow Lee et¬†al. (2015) and apply the sequential Monte Carlo (SMC) ABC scheme of Drovandi and Pettitt (2011). This algorithm is efficient, straightforward to implement, automatically selects the sequence of target distributions, and has intuitive stopping criteria. For simulating from the extremal-tùë°t and Brown-Resnick models, we employ the exact simulation algorithm via extremal functions developed by Dombry et¬†al. (2016).

The remainder of the paper is structured as follows. The models we considered are introduced in Section¬†2, and the ABC method is elaborated in Section¬†3. Implementation details specific to the data set, a description of the data set and the corresponding results as well as a simulation study are contained in Section¬†4. A discussion of the results along with limitations and possible extensions is provided in Section¬†5.

2 Spatial extremes models

2.1 Models and parameterisations

As stated in Section¬†1, statistical analysis of extremal data uses specialised models developed for such data. In this paper, we consider the use of spatial max-stable models to describe the spatial dependence of the South Australian maximum temperature data. Specifically, we investigate the following three stationary max-stable models: extremal-tùë°t model (Opitz, 2013) with either a Whittle-Mat√©rn or a powered exponential correlation function, and the Brown-Resnick model with power variogram (Brown and Resnick, 1977; Kabluchko et¬†al., 2009). Furthermore, we will consider to model the data using a non-extremal Student-tùë°t copula model (Demarta and McNeil, 2005) with unit Fr√©chet margins and either a Whittle-Mat√©rn or powered exponential correlation function.

Max-stable processes arise as the limiting process of normalised pointwise maxima over infinitely many independent copies of a stochastic processes. If such a limiting process exists, it has to be a max-stable process. That is, if ‚àÄùíô‚ààùí≥‚äÜ‚Ñùdfor-allùíôùí≥superscript‚Ñùùëë\forall\>\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{d} there exist normalising sequences {(an‚Äã(ùíô),bn‚Äã(ùíô)>0);n‚â•1}subscriptùëéùëõùíôsubscriptùëèùëõùíô0ùëõ1\{(a_{n}(\bm{x}),\,b_{n}(\bm{x})>0);\>n\geq 1\} such that for the normalised maxima of independent copies of the process {X‚Äã(ùíô),ùíô‚ààùí≥}ùëãùíôùíôùí≥\{X(\bm{x}),\>\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\} one has

maxi=1,‚Ä¶,n‚Å°{Xi‚Äã(ùíô)}‚àían‚Äã(ùíô)bn‚Äã(ùíô)‚Äã‚ü∂d‚ÄãZ‚Äã(ùíô),n‚Üí‚àû;ùíô‚ààùí≥‚äÜ‚Ñùd,formulae-sequence‚Üísubscriptùëñ1‚Ä¶ùëõsubscriptùëãùëñùíôsubscriptùëéùëõùíôsubscriptùëèùëõùíôd‚ü∂ùëçùíôùëõùíôùí≥superscript‚Ñùùëë\dfrac{\max_{i=1,\ldots,n}\{X_{i}(\bm{x})\}-a_{n}(\bm{x})}{b_{n}(\bm{x})}\overset{\mathrm{d}}{\longrightarrow}Z(\bm{x}),\quad n\rightarrow\infty;\quad\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{d},

then {Z‚Äã(ùíô),ùíô‚ààùí≥}ùëçùíôùíôùí≥\{Z(\bm{x}),\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\}, if not degenerate, is a max-stable process (de¬†Haan and Ferreira, 2006). The symbol ‚ü∂dd‚ü∂\overset{\mathrm{d}}{\longrightarrow} means convergence in distribution. The stochastic process obtained by taking the appropriately renormalised pointwise maxima over finitely many copies of a max-stable process is equal in distribution to the original max-stable process. The univariate marginal distributions of max-stable processes are members of the generalised extreme value (GEV) family. When dealing with max-stable processes, it is often assumed that all univariate margins have a unit Fr√©chet distribution (Pr‚Å°(Z‚Äã(ùíô)‚â§z)=exp‚Å°(‚àí1/z)Prùëçùíôùëß1ùëß\Pr(Z(\bm{x})\leq z)=\exp(-1/z)), while the focus is on modelling the dependence structure. It is possible to apply simple transformations to each margin to make the univariate margins follow any desired univariate GEV distribution. The converse transformations need to be applied to turn general GEV margins into unit Fr√©chet margins (see Section¬†2.2).

Their theoretical justification as limiting processes makes max-stable processes a popular choice for the modelling of extreme events in space. In practice, a spatio-temporal data series is usually divided into different blocks (e.g., years) according to the temporal dimension and the pointwise maxima within each block are computed for all locations. Only these pointwise maxima (e.g., annual maxima) are considered for modelling. If each block contains many observations and the different blocks are approximately independent, max-stable process models serve as reasonable approximations to the true spatial process. One does not need to model the unknown underlying process XùëãX.

Every max-stable process {Z‚Äã(ùíô),ùíô‚ààùí≥}ùëçùíôùíôùí≥\{Z(\bm{x}),\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\} with unit Fr√©chet margins possesses a spectral representation of the form

The Brown-Resnick process is specified by the semi-variogram Œ≥‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)ùõæsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2\gamma(\bm{x}_{1},\bm{x}_{2}) between any two locations ùíô1subscriptùíô1\bm{x}_{1} and ùíô2subscriptùíô2\bm{x}_{2}. Most often, the functional form Œ≥‚Äã(h)=(h/Œª)Œ∫ùõæ‚Ñésuperscript‚ÑéùúÜùúÖ\gamma(h)=\left(h/\lambda\right)^{\kappa} for Œª>0ùúÜ0\lambda>0 and 0<Œ∫‚â§20ùúÖ20<\kappa\leq 2 is assumed, in which case the process {œµ‚Äã(ùíô),ùíô‚ààùí≥}italic-œµùíôùíôùí≥\{\epsilon(\bm{x}),\>\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\} is a fractional Brownian motion. In our application, we will assume this form of the semi-variogram. The special case Œ∫=2ùúÖ2\kappa=2 corresponds to the well-known Smith model (Smith, 1990).

In addition to the max-stable extremal-tùë°t and Brown-Resnick models, we will also consider a non-extremal Student-tùë°t copula model with unit Fr√©chet marginal distributions. In that model, only the univariate marginal distributions are modelled by the limiting extremal unit Fr√©chet distribution (after transforming the margins accordingly), whereas the dependence structure is modelled by a standard non-extremal tùë°t copula without appealing to the asymptotic max-stable theory. Since the multivariate tùë°t distribution is an asymptotically dependent elliptical distribution, the limiting process of rescaled pointwise maxima of a Student-tùë°t process is the extremal-tùë°t process (Opitz, 2013). Therefore, the tùë°t copula model can be regarded as a tractable approximation to the extremal-tùë°t model.

According to Sklar‚Äôs Theorem (Nelsen, 2006; Joe, 1997), any joint distribution function F‚Äã(z1,‚Ä¶,zH)ùêπsubscriptùëß1‚Ä¶subscriptùëßùêªF(z_{1},\ldots,z_{H}) can be represented as

where C:[0,1]H‚Üí[0,1]:ùê∂‚Üísuperscript01ùêª01C:[0,1]^{H}\rightarrow[0,1] is the copula function defined on the unit hypercube and F1,‚Ä¶,FHsubscriptùêπ1‚Ä¶subscriptùêπùêªF_{1},\ldots,F_{H} are the univariate marginal distributions of FùêπF. The copula function itself is a multivariate distribution function with uniform margins. Therefore, copula models make it possible to model the joint distribution and the marginal distributions separately. If all the margins of FùêπF are absolutely continuous, then Cùê∂C is unique.

We will consider the Student-tùë°t copula (Demarta and McNeil, 2005), which is defined as

We will consider the same correlation functions as for the extremal-tùë°t model (Table¬†1).

The multivariate distributions given by the HùêªH-dimensional margins of the max-stable extremal-tùë°t and Brown-Resnick processes can also be regarded as copula models. However, their copulas are extremal copulas, which must satisfy the max-stable property (Joe, 1997)

C‚Äã(u1n,‚Ä¶,uHn)=Cn‚Äã(u1,‚Ä¶,uH),0<ui<1;i=1,‚Ä¶,H;n‚àà‚Ñï.formulae-sequenceformulae-sequenceùê∂superscriptsubscriptùë¢1ùëõ‚Ä¶superscriptsubscriptùë¢ùêªùëõsuperscriptùê∂ùëõsubscriptùë¢1‚Ä¶subscriptùë¢ùêª0subscriptùë¢ùëñ1formulae-sequenceùëñ1‚Ä¶ùêªùëõ‚ÑïC(u_{1}^{n},\ldots,u_{H}^{n})=C^{n}(u_{1},\ldots,u_{H}),\quad 0<u_{i}<1;\>i=1,\ldots,H;\>n\in\mathbb{N}.

The corresponding copulas for the extremal-tùë°t and the Brown-Resnick process are the tùë°t-EV copula (Demarta and McNeil, 2005) and the H√ºsler-Reiss copula (H√ºsler and Reiss, 1989), respectively.

The correlation functions of the extremal-tùë°t and tùë°t copula models and the semi-variogram of the Brown-Resnick model contain two parameters: the range (Œª)ùúÜ(\lambda) and smoothness (Œ∫)ùúÖ(\kappa) parameters. In addition, the extremal-tùë°t model and the tùë°t copula model have a degrees of freedom (dof) parameter, ŒΩ>0ùúà0\nu>0. Setting ŒΩ=1ùúà1\nu=1 for the extremal-tùë°t model yields the widely used Schlather model (Schlather, 2002).

If the distance h‚Ñéh is the Euclidean distance between two locations, all the models we consider are isotropic. We allow for geometric anisotropy by introducing an anisotropy matrix, which is determined by two additional parameters, see Blanchet and Davison (2011). Let ùíô1=(x1,1,x1,2)Tsubscriptùíô1superscriptsubscriptùë•11subscriptùë•12ùëá\bm{x}_{1}=(x_{1,1},\>x_{1,2})^{T} and ùíô2=(x2,1,x2,2)Tsubscriptùíô2superscriptsubscriptùë•21subscriptùë•22ùëá\bm{x}_{2}=(x_{2,1},\>x_{2,2})^{T} be two locations in ùí≥ùí≥\mathcal{X}. Then the distance h‚Ñéh between these two locations is defined as

h‚Äã(ùíô1‚àíùíô2)=‚Äñùë®‚Äã(ùíô1‚àíùíô2)‚Äñ,‚Ñésubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2normùë®subscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2h(\bm{x}_{1}-\bm{x}_{2})=\|\bm{A}\,(\bm{x}_{1}-\bm{x}_{2})\|,

where ‚à•‚ãÖ‚à•\|\cdot\| denotes Euclidean distance and the anisotropy matrix ùë®ùë®\bm{A} is given by

ùë®=(1001/r)‚ãÖ(cos‚Å°Œ±sin‚Å°Œ±‚àísin‚Å°Œ±cos‚Å°Œ±).ùë®‚ãÖmatrix1001ùëümatrixùõºùõºùõºùõº\bm{A}=\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\ 0&1/r\end{pmatrix}\cdot\begin{pmatrix}\cos\alpha&\sin\alpha\\ -\sin\alpha&\cos\alpha\end{pmatrix}.

Hence, we apply the isotropic models to the transformed space ùí≥¬Ø=ùë®‚Äãùí≥¬Øùí≥ùë®ùí≥\bar{\mathcal{X}}=\bm{A}\mathcal{X}. The two additional parameters governing the extent of geometric anisotropy are the counter-clockwise rotation angle Œ±ùõº\alpha of the correlation contour ellipse (0‚â§Œ±<œÄ/20ùõºùúã20\leq\alpha<\pi/2) and the ratio r>0ùëü0r>0 of the two principal axes of the correlation contour ellipse.

In our application we assume there is no nugget effect. That is, we assume there is no discontinuity in the correlation function or semi-variogram at h=0‚Ñé0h=0. This is a common assumption for environmental processes, see, e.g., Erhardt and Smith (2012) and Erhardt and Sisson (2015).

2.2 Marginal transformations to unit Fr√©chet

All the models we consider have unit Fr√©chet marginal distributions: Pr‚Å°(Z‚Äã(ùíô)‚â§z)=exp‚Å°(‚àí1/z)Prùëçùíôùëß1ùëß\Pr(Z(\bm{x})\leq z)=\exp\left(-1/z\right), z>0ùëß0z>0. In general, the limiting distribution for univariate extremal data is from the class of generalised extreme value distributions, which are determined by a location (Œº‚àà‚Ñùùúá‚Ñù\mu\in\mathbb{R}), scale (œÉ>0ùúé0\sigma>0), and shape (Œæ‚àà‚Ñùùúâ‚Ñù\xi\in\mathbb{R}) parameter (Ribatet, 2013): for Z‚àó‚Äã(ùíô)‚àºG‚ÄãE‚ÄãV‚Äã(Œº,œÉ,Œæ)similar-tosuperscriptùëçùíôùê∫ùê∏ùëâùúáùúéùúâZ^{*}(\bm{x})\sim GEV(\mu,\sigma,\xi),

Pr‚Å°(Z‚àó‚Äã(ùíô)‚â§z)=exp‚Å°{‚àí[1+Œæ‚Äãz‚àíŒºœÉ]‚àí1Œæ}.Prsuperscriptùëçùíôùëßsuperscriptdelimited-[]1ùúâùëßùúáùúé1ùúâ\Pr(Z^{*}(\bm{x})\leq z)=\exp\left\{-\left[1+\xi\>\frac{z-\mu}{\sigma}\right]^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}\right\}.

However, it is straightforward to transform Z‚àó‚Äã(ùíô)‚àºG‚ÄãE‚ÄãV‚Äã(Œº,œÉ,Œæ)similar-tosuperscriptùëçùíôùê∫ùê∏ùëâùúáùúéùúâZ^{*}(\bm{x})\sim GEV(\mu,\sigma,\xi) to a unit Fr√©chet random variable Z‚Äã(ùíô)‚àºG‚ÄãE‚ÄãV‚Äã(1,1,1)similar-toùëçùíôùê∫ùê∏ùëâ111Z(\bm{x})\sim GEV(1,1,1):

Z‚Äã(ùíô)=(1+Œæ‚ÄãZ‚àó‚Äã(ùíô)‚àíŒºœÉ)1Œæ.ùëçùíôsuperscript1ùúâsuperscriptùëçùíôùúáùúé1ùúâZ(\bm{x})=\left(1+\xi\>\frac{Z^{*}(\bm{x})-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{\frac{1}{\xi}}. (2.2)

For real data, we first estimate the marginal GEV parameters at each location by maximum likelihood and then apply transformation (2.2) to the data to (approximately) obtain unit Fr√©chet margins. A nonparametric alternative, which we do not pursue, would be to apply the inverse probability integral transform of the unit Fr√©chet distribution to the observations‚Äô rank-based empirical cumulative distribution function values at each location.

2.3 Indicators of dependence structure

The viability of approximate Bayesian computation depends on the availability of informative and easy-to-compute summary statistics of the data. Our summary statistics will incorporate empirical estimates of F-madograms, pairwise and tripletwise extremal coefficients, and Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau, as well as composite score vectors for all the models considered. Unfortunately, none of these statistics is sufficient for the parameters of any of the models. In order to obtain summary statistics for the ABC procedure that contain as much information about the process as possible, we collect a large set of informative statistics and aggregate them in a sensible way using the Fearnhead-Prangle procedure (see Sections¬†3.2 and 4.1). Even if various dependence indicators provide partly redundant information, it may prove worthwhile to include all of them to the set of summary statistics. The redundant information will be filtered out by the Fearnhead-Prangle procedure.

The F-madogram (Cooley et¬†al., 2006) is similar to the semi-variogram. The theoretical variogram is not always defined for a max-stable process due to the possibility of a non-finite mean or variance. The F-madogram is always well-defined and is given by

ŒΩF‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)=12‚ÄãE‚Äã[|Fùíô1‚Äã{Z‚Äã(ùíô1)}‚àíFùíô2‚Äã{Z‚Äã(ùíô2)}|],subscriptùúàùêπsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô212ùê∏delimited-[]subscriptùêπsubscriptùíô1ùëçsubscriptùíô1subscriptùêπsubscriptùíô2ùëçsubscriptùíô2\nu_{F}(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})=\frac{1}{2}E\left[|F_{\bm{x}_{1}}\left\{Z(\bm{x}_{1})\right\}-F_{\bm{x}_{2}}\left\{Z(\bm{x}_{2})\right\}|\right],

where Fùíô1subscriptùêπsubscriptùíô1F_{\bm{x}_{1}} and Fùíô2subscriptùêπsubscriptùíô2F_{\bm{x}_{2}} are the cumulative distribution functions (CDFs) of the random variable Z‚Äã(ùíô)ùëçùíôZ(\bm{x}) at locations ùíô1subscriptùíô1\bm{x}_{1} and ùíô2subscriptùíô2\bm{x}_{2}, respectively. As we assume that all marginal distributions of our transformed data are unit Fr√©chet, the F-madogram can easily be estimated by

ŒΩ^F‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)=12‚Äãn‚Äã‚àëi=1n|F‚Äã(Zi‚Äã(ùíô1))‚àíF‚Äã(Zi‚Äã(ùíô2))|,subscript^ùúàùêπsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô212ùëõsuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùëõùêπsubscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíô1ùêπsubscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíô2\hat{\nu}_{F}(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})=\frac{1}{2n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}|F(Z_{i}(\bm{x}_{1}))-F(Z_{i}(\bm{x}_{2}))|,

where nùëõn is the number of observed extremal process realisations at each location, Zi‚Äã(ùíôj)subscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíôùëóZ_{i}(\bm{x}_{j}) is the observed value at location jùëój, and F‚Äã(z)=exp‚Å°(‚àí1/z)ùêπùëß1ùëßF(z)=\exp(-1/z) is the unit Fr√©chet CDF. In case the marginal distributions are unknown, a nonparametric estimator based on the ranks is commonly used (see Ribatet (2013)).

For max-stable processes, the extremal coefficient Œ∏‚Äã(ùíô1,‚Ä¶,ùíôL)ùúÉsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶subscriptùíôùêø\theta(\bm{x}_{1},\ldots,\bm{x}_{L}) (Schlather and Tawn, 2003) is another measure of spatial dependence between a subset of LùêøL locations. We will consider pairwise (L=2ùêø2L=2) and tripletwise (L=3ùêø3L=3) extremal coefficients. Assuming unit Fr√©chet marginal distributions of the process {Z‚Äã(ùíô),ùíô‚ààùí≥}ùëçùíôùíôùí≥\{Z(\bm{x}),\>\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\}, the pairwise extremal coefficient between the locations ùíô1,ùíô2,‚Ä¶,ùíôLsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2‚Ä¶subscriptùíôùêø\bm{x}_{1},\bm{x}_{2},\ldots,\bm{x}_{L} is defined by the relation

Pr‚Å°(Z‚Äã(ùíô1)‚â§z,‚Ä¶,Z‚Äã(ùíôL)‚â§z)Prùëçsubscriptùíô1ùëß‚Ä¶ùëçsubscriptùíôùêøùëß\displaystyle\Pr(Z(\bm{x}_{1})\leq z,\ldots,Z(\bm{x}_{L})\leq z) =\displaystyle= Pr(Z(ùíô1)‚â§z)Œ∏‚Äã(ùíô1,‚Ä¶,ùíôL)\displaystyle\Pr(Z(\bm{x}_{1})\leq z)^{\theta(\bm{x}_{1},\ldots,\bm{x}_{L})} (2.3)
=\displaystyle= exp‚Å°(‚àíŒ∏‚Äã(ùíô1,‚Ä¶,ùíôL)z).ùúÉsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶subscriptùíôùêøùëß\displaystyle\exp\left(-\frac{\theta(\bm{x}_{1},\ldots,\bm{x}_{L})}{z}\right).

An extremal coefficient value of 111 indicates complete dependence between the observations, whereas the value of LùêøL indicates complete independence.

Note that the extremal coefficient function does not fully characterise the max-stable process (see Strokorb et¬†al. (2015)), a notable exception being the Tawn-Molchanov process (Strokorb and Schlather, 2015).

Coles et¬†al. (1999) propose a simple and fast-to-compute estimator for the pairwise extremal coefficient. Erhardt and Smith (2012) generalise the estimator to an arbitrary number of locations. Their proposed extremal coefficient estimator is

Œ∏^‚Äã(ùíô1,‚Ä¶,ùíôL)=n‚àëi=1n1/max‚Å°{Zi‚Äã(ùíô1),‚Ä¶,Zi‚Äã(ùíôL)},^ùúÉsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶subscriptùíôùêøùëõsuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùëõ1subscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶subscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíôùêø\hat{\theta}(\bm{x}_{1},\ldots,\bm{x}_{L})=\frac{n}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}{1/\max\{Z_{i}(\bm{x}_{1}),\ldots,Z_{i}(\bm{x}_{L})\}}}, (2.4)

when there are nùëõn independent copies of the max-stable process and Zi‚Äã(ùíôj)subscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíôùëóZ_{i}(\bm{x}_{j}) denotes the iùëñi-th copy of the process observed at location ùíôjsubscriptùíôùëó\bm{x}_{j}.

This estimator is easily derived by observing that the random variable
1/max‚Å°{Z‚Äã(ùíô1),‚Ä¶,Z‚Äã(ùíôL)}1ùëçsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶ùëçsubscriptùíôùêø1/\max\{Z(\bm{x}_{1}),\ldots,Z(\bm{x}_{L})\} has an exponential distribution with rate parameter Œ∏‚Äã(ùíô1,‚Ä¶,ùíôL)ùúÉsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶subscriptùíôùêø\theta(\bm{x}_{1},\ldots,\bm{x}_{L}). It follows that estimator (2.4) is the maximum likelihood estimator of the rate parameter.

The extremal coefficient as given by Equation¬†(2.3) is only defined for max-stable models. For other models with unit Fr√©chet margins such as the tùë°t copula model, the value of Œ∏ùúÉ\theta in

Pr(Z(ùíô1)‚â§z,‚Ä¶,Z(ùíôL)‚â§z)=Pr(Z(ùíô1)‚â§z)Œ∏\Pr(Z(\bm{x}_{1})\leq z,\ldots,Z(\bm{x}_{L})\leq z)=\Pr(Z(\bm{x}_{1})\leq z)^{\theta}

depends on the level zùëßz. However, estimator¬†(2.4) is still a useful measure of dependency. If the distribution of the random variable U=1/max‚Å°{Z‚Äã(ùíô1),‚Ä¶,Z‚Äã(ùíôL)}=ùëà1ùëçsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶ùëçsubscriptùíôùêøabsentU=1/\max\{Z(\bm{x}_{1}),\ldots,Z(\bm{x}_{L})\}=
min‚Å°{1/Z‚Äã(ùíô1),‚Ä¶,1/Z‚Äã(ùíôL)}1ùëçsubscriptùíô1‚Ä¶1ùëçsubscriptùíôùêø\min\{1/Z(\bm{x}_{1}),\ldots,1/Z(\bm{x}_{L})\} is approximated by an exponential distribution, then estimator¬†(2.4) provides an estimate for its rate parameter. In the limiting cases of complete dependence and complete independence, the distribution of UùëàU is exactly exponential with rate parameters 111 and LùêøL, respectively, just as for max-stable processes. For simplicity, we will generally refer to the summary statistics Œ∏^^ùúÉ\hat{\theta} computed using Equation¬†(2.4) as extremal coefficient estimates, even though only max-stable processes possess an extremal coefficient as defined by Equation¬†(2.3).

There are other estimators for the extremal coefficients with better estimation properties. For max-stable processes, there is a one-to-one relationship between the pairwise extremal coefficient and the F-madogram,

Œ∏‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)=1+2‚ÄãŒΩF‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)1‚àí2‚ÄãŒΩF‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2),ùúÉsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô212subscriptùúàùêπsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô212subscriptùúàùêπsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2\theta(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})=\frac{1+2\,\nu_{F}(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})}{1-2\,\nu_{F}(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})},

which can be exploited to construct an estimator. We do not consider this estimator because we already include estimates for the pairwise F-madograms in our set of summary statistics. Two further estimators are proposed by Schlather and Tawn (2003). These estimators are self-consistent and satisfy the boundary conditions, whereas the estimates given by (2.4) and the estimates constructed via the F-madogram can fall outside the theoretical bounds.

However, our purpose is to use the extremal coefficients as summary statistics in ABC in order to assess the similarity of data sets. The estimates do not need to adhere to the theoretical properties to be useful for that purpose. Since we will aggregate the estimates across many location pairs and triplets for our summary statistics (see Section¬†4.1), we are also not particularly concerned about estimator efficiency or self-consistency. It is more important that the estimates can be computed quickly, which is the case for estimator (2.4).

Another dependence measure we consider is Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau between any pair of locations, which is estimated by

œÑ^‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)=2n‚Äã(n‚àí1)‚Äã‚àë1‚â§i<j‚â§nsign‚Äã[Zi‚Äã(ùíô1)‚àíZj‚Äã(ùíô1)]‚Äãsign‚Äã[Zi‚Äã(ùíô2)‚àíZj‚Äã(ùíô2)],^ùúèsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô22ùëõùëõ1subscript1ùëñùëóùëõsigndelimited-[]subscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíô1subscriptùëçùëósubscriptùíô1signdelimited-[]subscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùíô2subscriptùëçùëósubscriptùíô2\hat{\tau}(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})=\frac{2}{n\,(n-1)}\sum_{1\leq i<j\leq n}\mathrm{sign}[Z_{i}(\bm{x}_{1})-Z_{j}(\bm{x}_{1})]\>\mathrm{sign}[Z_{i}(\bm{x}_{2})-Z_{j}(\bm{x}_{2})],

where {Zi‚Äã(ùíô);ùíô‚ààùí≥;i=1,‚Ä¶,n}formulae-sequencesubscriptùëçùëñùíôùíôùí≥ùëñ1‚Ä¶ùëõ\{Z_{i}(\bm{x});\>\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X};\>i=1,\ldots,n\} are nùëõn observed copies of the process. Dombry et¬†al. (2017c) show that for max-stable processes Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau is equal to the pairwise extremal concurrence probability. This is the probability that the extremal occurrences at two locations ùíô1subscriptùíô1\bm{x}_{1} and ùíô2subscriptùíô2\bm{x}_{2} are obtained from the same spectral function (cf. Equation¬†(2.1)):

œÑ‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)=Pr‚Å°(arg‚Å°maxi‚â•1‚ÄãŒ∂i‚ÄãYi‚Äã(ùíô1)=arg‚Å°maxi‚â•1‚ÄãŒ∂i‚ÄãYi‚Äã(ùíô2)).ùúèsubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2Prùëñ1subscriptùúÅùëñsubscriptùëåùëñsubscriptùíô1ùëñ1subscriptùúÅùëñsubscriptùëåùëñsubscriptùíô2\tau(\bm{x}_{1},\,\bm{x}_{2})=\Pr\left(\underset{i\geq 1}{\arg\max}\>\zeta_{i}Y_{i}(\bm{x}_{1})=\underset{i\geq 1}{\arg\max}\>\zeta_{i}Y_{i}(\bm{x}_{2})\right).

2.4 Composite score vector

Our summary statistics will also incorporate the composite score vectors for all the models. Ruli et¬†al. (2016) prove that the score vector is a sufficient summary statistic for the parameters of exponential models. Therefore, one can expect that the score vector also provides informative summary statistics for the parameters of many non-exponential models.

In the case of max-stable models, the density functions and hence log-likelihood functions are intractable for moderate to high dimensions for most models. Therefore, classical inference for max-stable models is commonly based on the composite likelihood approach (Padoan et¬†al., 2010). A composite log-likelihood is a weighted sum of log-likelihoods for marginal or conditional events. For max-stable models, the composite likelihood is usually constructed from pairwise likelihoods. Given nùëõn independent copies of the process observed at HùêªH locations, the pairwise log-likelihood is defined to be

p‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï;ùíÅ)=‚àëk=1n‚àëi=1H‚àí1‚àëj=i+1Hwi‚Äãj‚Äã‚Ñìi‚Äãj‚Äã{œï;Zk‚Äã(ùíôi),Zk‚Äã(ùíôj)},ùëù‚Ñìbold-italic-œïùíÅsuperscriptsubscriptùëò1ùëõsuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùêª1superscriptsubscriptùëóùëñ1ùêªsubscriptùë§ùëñùëósubscript‚Ñìùëñùëóbold-italic-œïsubscriptùëçùëòsubscriptùíôùëñsubscriptùëçùëòsubscriptùíôùëóp\ell(\bm{\phi};\bm{Z})=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\sum_{i=1}^{H-1}\sum_{j=i+1}^{H}w_{ij}\ell_{ij}\{\bm{\phi};Z_{k}(\bm{x}_{i}),Z_{k}(\bm{x}_{j})\}, (2.5)

where ùíÅ={Zk(ùíôi);k=1,‚Ä¶,n;i=1,‚Ä¶,H}\bm{Z}=\{Z_{k}(\bm{x}_{i});\>k=1,\ldots,n;\>i=1,\ldots,H\} are the observations, œïbold-italic-œï\bm{\phi} is the vector of parameters, ‚Ñìi‚Äãj‚Äã{œï;Zk‚Äã(ùíôi),Zk‚Äã(ùíôj)}subscript‚Ñìùëñùëóbold-italic-œïsubscriptùëçùëòsubscriptùíôùëñsubscriptùëçùëòsubscriptùíôùëó\ell_{ij}\{\bm{\phi};Z_{k}(\bm{x}_{i}),Z_{k}(\bm{x}_{j})\} is the bivariate marginal log-likelihood contribution of process copy kùëòk observed at locations iùëñi and jùëój, and the wi‚Äãjsubscriptùë§ùëñùëów_{ij} are weights (all set to 1 in our application). The composite score vector is

ùíî‚Äã(ùíÅ;œï)=‚àáœïp‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï;ùíÅ).ùíîùíÅbold-italic-œïsubscript‚àábold-italic-œïùëù‚Ñìbold-italic-œïùíÅ\bm{s}(\bm{Z};\bm{\phi})=\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}\;p\ell(\bm{\phi};\bm{Z}).

The maximum composite likelihood estimator (MCLE) is œï~=arg‚Å°maxœï‚Å°p‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï;ùíÅ)~bold-italic-œïsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëù‚Ñìbold-italic-œïùíÅ\tilde{\bm{\phi}}=\arg\max_{\bm{\phi}}\>p\ell(\bm{\phi};\bm{Z}), which is obtained by either maximising p‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï;ùíÅ)ùëù‚Ñìbold-italic-œïùíÅp\ell(\bm{\phi};\bm{Z}) directly or by solving ùíî‚Äã(ùíÅ;œï)=ùüéùíîùíÅbold-italic-œï0\bm{s}(\bm{Z};\bm{\phi})=\bm{0}. Under the usual regularity conditions on the bivariate marginal likelihoods, ùíî‚Äã(ùíÅ;œï)=ùüéùíîùíÅbold-italic-œï0\bm{s}(\bm{Z};\bm{\phi})=\bm{0} is a system of unbiased estimating equations because ùíî‚Äã(ùíÅ;œï)ùíîùíÅbold-italic-œï\bm{s}(\bm{Z};\bm{\phi}) is the sum over the proper score vectors of the bivariate marginal distributions (Varin, 2008). The MCLE œï~~bold-italic-œï\tilde{\bm{\phi}} is consistent and asymptotically normal under rather broad assumptions (Molenberghs and Verbeke, 2005).

Ruli et¬†al. (2016) use ùíî‚Äã(ùíÅ;œï~obs)ùíîùíÅsubscript~bold-italic-œïobs\bm{s}(\bm{Z};\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{\mathrm{obs}}) as summary statistic for ABC, where
œï~obs=arg‚Å°maxœï‚Å°p‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï;ùíõobs)subscript~bold-italic-œïobssubscriptbold-italic-œïùëù‚Ñìbold-italic-œïsubscriptùíõobs\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{\mathrm{obs}}=\arg\max_{\bm{\phi}}\>p\ell(\bm{\phi};\bm{z}_{\mathrm{obs}}) and ùíõobssubscriptùíõobs\bm{z}_{\mathrm{obs}} is the observed data. This summary statistic can be calculated quickly for any new simulated data set ùíÅùíÅ\bm{Z} because œï~obssubscript~bold-italic-œïobs\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{\mathrm{obs}} has to be computed only once. Note that the value of the summary statistic for the observed data is ùíî‚Äã(ùíõobs;œï~obs)=ùüéùíîsubscriptùíõobssubscript~bold-italic-œïobs0\bm{s}(\bm{z}_{\mathrm{obs}};\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{\mathrm{obs}})=\mathbf{0} by definition of œï~obssubscript~bold-italic-œïobs\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{\mathrm{obs}} apart from numerical inaccuracies in practice.

The marginal bivariate log-likelihood and score functions are given in Appendices¬†I and J.

3 Approximate Bayesian computation for model selection and parameter estimation

3.1 Introduction to ABC

Approximate Bayesian computation (ABC) methods rely on model simulation to conduct approximate Bayesian inference and are particularly useful in circumventing analytically or computationally intractable likelihood evaluations. Spatial extremes analysis is one of many applied disciplines where ABC has been used (Erhardt and Sisson, 2015).

ABC avoids likelihood evaluations by retaining parameter draws that generate simulated data close to the observed data. To avoid the curse of dimensionality, the comparison is typically via a lower-dimensional summary statistic (Blum, 2010).

Our goal is to obtain posterior inference for the combined objective of model selection and parameter estimation. We consider a model setup with KùêæK possible models that could have generated the data. The discrete model indicator random variable ‚Ñ≥‚Ñ≥\mathcal{M} can assume the values k=0,‚Ä¶,K‚àí1ùëò0‚Ä¶ùêæ1k=0,\ldots,K-1 with prior probabilities Pr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=k)Pr‚Ñ≥ùëò\Pr(\mathcal{M}=k), which have to satisfy ‚àëk=0K‚àí1Pr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=k)=1superscriptsubscriptùëò0ùêæ1Pr‚Ñ≥ùëò1\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}\Pr(\mathcal{M}=k)=1. For each model, the (intractable) likelihood function is denoted by fk(‚ãÖ|œïk)f_{k}(\cdot|\,\bm{\phi}_{k}), which depends on the model-specific parameter vector œïksubscriptbold-italic-œïùëò\bm{\phi}_{k} having prior distribution œÄ‚Äã(œïk|‚Ñ≥=k)ùúãconditionalsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëò‚Ñ≥ùëò\pi(\bm{\phi}_{k}|\,\mathcal{M}=k). The observed data ùíõùíõ\bm{z} and the simulated data ùíñùíñ\bm{u} are compared via the discrepancy function d‚Äã[‚ãÖ,‚ãÖ]ùëë‚ãÖ‚ãÖd[\cdot,\cdot] applied to the summary statistics ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ)ùíïùíõ\bm{t}(\bm{z}) and ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ)ùíïùíñ\bm{t}(\bm{u}). Given a tolerance level œµitalic-œµ\epsilon for accepting simulated draws, the targeted approximate posterior density has the form

œÄœµ‚Äã(œïk,k|ùíõ)‚àùPr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=k)‚ÄãœÄ‚Äã(œïk|‚Ñ≥=k)‚Äã‚à´ùíñ‚ààùíµfk‚Äã(ùíñ|œïk)‚Äã‚ÄÖ1‚Äã{d‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ)]<œµ}‚Äãdùíñ,proportional-tosubscriptùúãitalic-œµsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëòconditionalùëòùíõPr‚Ñ≥ùëòùúãconditionalsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëò‚Ñ≥ùëòsubscriptùíñùíµsubscriptùëìùëòconditionalùíñsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëò1ùëëùíïùíõùíïùíñitalic-œµdifferential-dùíñ\pi_{\epsilon}(\bm{\phi}_{k},k|\,\bm{z})\propto\Pr(\mathcal{M}=k)\>\pi(\bm{\phi}_{k}|\,\mathcal{M}=k)\>\int_{\bm{u}\in\mathcal{Z}}\,f_{k}(\bm{u}|\,\bm{\phi}_{k})\>\mathds{1}\{d[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u})]<\epsilon\}\>\mathrm{d}\bm{u}, (3.1)

where ùüô‚Äã{d‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ)]<œµ}1ùëëùíïùíõùíïùíñitalic-œµ\mathds{1}\{d[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u})]<\epsilon\} is the indicator function which is 1 if d‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ)]<œµùëëùíïùíõùíïùíñitalic-œµd[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u})]<\epsilon and 0 otherwise. If the summary statistics ùíï‚Äã(‚ãÖ)ùíï‚ãÖ\bm{t}(\cdot) are sufficient for all the model parameters and the model indicator and œµ‚Üí0‚Üíitalic-œµ0\epsilon\rightarrow 0 when d‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ)]‚â•0‚Äã‚àÄùíõ,ùíñ‚ààùíµformulae-sequenceùëëùíïùíõùíïùíñ0for-allùíõùíñùíµd[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u})]\geq 0\;\forall\>\bm{z},\bm{u}\in\mathcal{Z}, one obtains the true joint posterior of parameters and model indicators.

Frazier et¬†al. (2018) provide large-sample asymptotic results for ABC concerning consistency, the shape of the posterior distribution, and the asymptotic distribution of the posterior mean under rather general conditions on the convergence of the summary statistics and the rate of œµ‚Üí0‚Üíitalic-œµ0\epsilon\rightarrow 0. See also Li and Fearnhead (2018) for similar results for the posterior mean. Marin et¬†al. (2014) present necessary and sufficient conditions on the summary statistics for consistent model choice.

The first ABC algorithm that was proposed (Pritchard et¬†al., 1999; Beaumont et¬†al., 2002) uses a rejection sampling scheme where the parameters are always drawn from the prior distribution. This scheme is hence referred to as rejection ABC. When extended to account for model selection, the algorithm works as follows: generate NùëÅN draws {ki,œïi}i=1Nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptùëòùëñsuperscriptbold-italic-œïùëñùëñ1ùëÅ\{k^{i},\bm{\phi}^{i}\}_{i=1}^{N} by simulating k‚àó‚àºPr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=k)similar-tosuperscriptùëòPr‚Ñ≥ùëòk^{*}\sim\Pr(\mathcal{M}=k), œïk‚àó‚àó‚àºœÄ‚Äã(œïk‚àó|‚Ñ≥=k‚àó)similar-tosuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùúãconditionalsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëò‚Ñ≥superscriptùëò\bm{\phi}_{k^{*}}^{*}\sim\pi(\bm{\phi}_{k^{*}}|\,\mathcal{M}=k^{*}), ùíñ‚àó‚àºfk‚àó‚Äã(ùíñ|œïk‚àó‚àó)similar-tosuperscriptùíñsubscriptùëìsuperscriptùëòconditionalùíñsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëò\bm{u}^{*}\sim f_{k^{*}}(\bm{u}|\,\bm{\phi}_{k^{*}}^{*}) and accepting (k‚àó,œïk‚àó‚àó)superscriptùëòsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëò(k^{*},\bm{\phi}_{k^{*}}^{*}) if d‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ‚àó)]<œµùëëùíïùíõùíïsuperscriptùíñitalic-œµd[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u}^{*})]<\epsilon until NùëÅN draws are accepted.

Markov chain Monte Carlo ABC (MCMC ABC) (Marjoram et¬†al., 2003) and later sequential Monte Carlo ABC (SMC ABC) (Beaumont et¬†al., 2009; Toni et¬†al., 2009; Sisson et¬†al., 2007, 2009; Drovandi and Pettitt, 2011) were proposed to alleviate the computational burden of rejection ABC by using more efficient parameter proposal distributions to explore the parameter and model space. We use the SMC ABC algorithm of Drovandi and Pettitt (2011) for our application.

3.2 Fearnhead-Prangle step

The ‚Äòsemi-automatic‚Äô summary statistic selection schemes proposed in Fearnhead and Prangle (2012) for parameter estimation and Prangle et¬†al. (2014) for model selection provide valuable strategies for selecting low-dimensional yet informative summary statistics.

Prangle et¬†al. (2014) prove that the posterior model probabilities form Bayes sufficient statistics for model selection, which is important to avoid the ABC model choice inaccuracies reported by Robert et¬†al. (2011). Bayes sufficiency of a statistic ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ)ùíïùíõ\bm{t}(\bm{z}) means that œï|ùíõconditionalbold-italic-œïùíõ\bm{\phi}|\,\bm{z} and œï|ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ)conditionalbold-italic-œïùíïùíõ\bm{\phi}|\,\bm{t}(\bm{z}) have the same posterior distribution for any prior distribution and almost all ùíõùíõ\bm{z} (Prangle et¬†al., 2014, p.¬†70). Therefore, Prangle et¬†al. (2014) propose to construct an estimator of the posterior model probabilities in a preliminary step to the actual ABC algorithm and use the estimated posterior model probabilities as summary statistics in ABC. The posterior model probabilities are estimated based on a set of available statistics ùíà‚Äã(ùíõ)=(g1‚Äã(ùíõ),‚Ä¶,gp‚Äã(ùíõ))Tùíàùíõsuperscriptsubscriptùëî1ùíõ‚Ä¶subscriptùëîùëùùíõùëá\bm{g}(\bm{z})=(g_{1}(\bm{z}),\ldots,g_{p}(\bm{z}))^{T}. Lee et¬†al. (2015) call this preliminary step the Fearnhead-Prangle (FP) step.

First, Prangle et¬†al. (2014) and Lee et¬†al. (2015) simulate a large training particle set {ki,œïkii,ùíñi}i=1Msuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptùëòùëñsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñùëñsuperscriptùíñùëñùëñ1ùëÄ\{k^{i},\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}^{i},\bm{u}^{i}\}_{i=1}^{M} generated from the prior predictive distribution: ki‚àºPr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=k)similar-tosuperscriptùëòùëñPr‚Ñ≥ùëòk^{i}\sim\Pr(\mathcal{M}=k), œïkii‚àºœÄ‚Äã(œïki|‚Ñ≥=ki)similar-tosuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñùëñùúãconditionalsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñ‚Ñ≥superscriptùëòùëñ\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}^{i}\sim\pi(\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}|\,\mathcal{M}=k^{i}), ùíñi‚àºfki‚Äã(ùíñ|œïkii)similar-tosuperscriptùíñùëñsubscriptùëìsuperscriptùëòùëñconditionalùíñsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñùëñ\bm{u}^{i}\sim f_{k^{i}}(\bm{u}|\,\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}^{i}). That is, each particle is a random draw from the joint distribution of the model indicator, the parameters, and the simulated data. Next, they regress the model indicators kisuperscriptùëòùëñk^{i} on the available statistics ùíà‚Äã(ùíñi)ùíàsuperscriptùíñùëñ\bm{g}(\bm{u}^{i}) of the simulated data to obtain an estimator of the model probabilities. Lee et¬†al. (2015) perform a backward stepwise procedure to exclude regressors in ùíà‚Äã(ùíñ)ùíàùíñ\bm{g}(\bm{u}) with little or no explanatory power for the model indicators. In an application with two models to choose from, Prangle et¬†al. (2014) propose to use logistic regression. Lee et¬†al. (2015) generalise the method to K>2ùêæ2K>2 models ‚Ñ≥=0,‚Ä¶,K‚àí1‚Ñ≥0‚Ä¶ùêæ1\mathcal{M}=0,\ldots,K-1 by fitting a multinomial logistic regression model,

log‚Å°(Pr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=k|ùíñ)1‚àí‚àëi=1K‚àí1Pr‚Å°(‚Ñ≥=i|ùíñ))=Œ≤0,k+‚àëi=1pŒ≤i,k‚Äãgi‚Äã(ùíñ),k=1,‚Ä¶,K‚àí1.formulae-sequencePr‚Ñ≥conditionalùëòùíñ1superscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùêæ1Pr‚Ñ≥conditionalùëñùíñsubscriptùõΩ0ùëòsuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùëùsubscriptùõΩùëñùëòsubscriptùëîùëñùíñùëò1‚Ä¶ùêæ1\log\left(\frac{\Pr(\mathcal{M}=k|\,\bm{u})}{1-\sum_{i=1}^{K-1}\Pr(\mathcal{M}=i|\,\bm{u})}\right)=\beta_{0,k}+\sum_{i=1}^{p}\beta_{i,k}\,g_{i}(\bm{u}),\quad k=1,\ldots,K-1. (3.2)

In the ABC step, this fit is used to estimate the posterior model probabilities for any sample ùíñ‚àósuperscriptùíñ\bm{u}^{*} generated during the procedure. This means the data is reduced to a (K‚àí1)ùêæ1(K-1)-dimensional summary statistic

where
