The same transformation is applied to the observed data ùíõùíõ\bm{z}.

If a pilot ABC study has been conducted, it is possible to truncate the parameter priors to accommodate the region of high posterior mass identified by the pilot study. By fitting the regression to a more localised sample, the regression fit is likely to improve. When simulating from truncated priors, a truncation correction has to be performed on the ABC output (Prangle et¬†al., 2014, p.¬†73).

For parameter estimation, Fearnhead and Prangle (2012) propose a similar ‚Äòsemi-automatic‚Äô scheme. They show that the choice of the quadratic error loss function yields the posterior mean as the optimal ABC summary statistic for continuous parameters when œµ‚Üí0‚Üíitalic-œµ0\epsilon\rightarrow 0. Consequently, for each single parameter in œïk=(œïk,1,‚Ä¶,œïk,Qk)Tsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëòsuperscriptsubscriptitalic-œïùëò1‚Ä¶subscriptitalic-œïùëòsubscriptùëÑùëòùëá\bm{\phi}_{k}=(\phi_{k,1},\ldots,\phi_{k,Q_{k}})^{T}, we follow Fearnhead and Prangle (2012) and Lee et¬†al. (2015) and run a backward stepwise linear regression of œïk,jisuperscriptsubscriptitalic-œïùëòùëóùëñ\phi_{k,j}^{i} (j=1,‚Ä¶,Qkùëó1‚Ä¶subscriptùëÑùëòj=1,\ldots,Q_{k}) on ùíà‚Äã(ùíñi)ùíàsuperscriptùíñùëñ\bm{g}(\bm{u}^{i}) based on the training particle subset {ki,œïkii,ùíñi:ki=k}i=1Msuperscriptsubscriptconditional-setsuperscriptùëòùëñsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñùëñsuperscriptùíñùëñsuperscriptùëòùëñùëòùëñ1ùëÄ\{k^{i},\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}^{i},\bm{u}^{i}:\>k^{i}=k\}_{i=1}^{M}. That is, we use the prior predictive samples from model kùëòk to estimate the regression functions for the posterior means of the parameters of model kùëòk. To reduce the computational expenditure, we re-use the training particle set generated for estimating the posterior model probabilities. In the ABC step, the summary statistic consists of the collection of estimates ùíïP(ùíñ)={œï^k,j(ùíñ);k=0,‚Ä¶,K‚àí1;j=1,‚Ä¶,Qk}\bm{t}_{P}(\bm{u})=\{\hat{\phi}_{k,j}(\bm{u});\>k=0,\ldots,K-1;\>j=1,\ldots,Q_{k}\}, where

œï^k,j‚Äã(ùíñ)=Œ≤^0,k,j+‚àëi=1pŒ≤^i,k,j‚Äãgi‚Äã(ùíñ).subscript^italic-œïùëòùëóùíñsubscript^ùõΩ0ùëòùëósuperscriptsubscriptùëñ1ùëùsubscript^ùõΩùëñùëòùëósubscriptùëîùëñùíñ\hat{\phi}_{k,j}(\bm{u})=\hat{\beta}_{0,k,j}+\sum_{i=1}^{p}\hat{\beta}_{i,k,j}\,g_{i}(\bm{u}). (3.3)

Therefore, the dimension of the summary statistic for parameter estimation is ‚àëk=0K‚àí1Qksuperscriptsubscriptùëò0ùêæ1subscriptùëÑùëò\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}Q_{k}.

We use the squared Euclidean distance as a discrepancy function for both model selection and parameter estimation. The model selection discrepancy is

dM‚Äã[ùíïM‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíïM‚Äã(ùíñ)]=‚àëk=1K‚àí1[Pr^‚Äã(‚Ñ≥=k|ùíõ)‚àíPr^‚Äã(‚Ñ≥=k|ùíñ)]2subscriptùëëùëÄsubscriptùíïùëÄùíõsubscriptùíïùëÄùíñsuperscriptsubscriptùëò1ùêæ1superscriptdelimited-[]^Pr‚Ñ≥conditionalùëòùíõ^Pr‚Ñ≥conditionalùëòùíñ2d_{M}[\bm{t}_{M}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}_{M}(\bm{u})]=\sum_{k=1}^{K-1}\left[\widehat{\Pr}(\mathcal{M}=k|\,\bm{z})-\widehat{\Pr}(\mathcal{M}=k|\,\bm{u})\right]^{2}

and the parameter estimation discrepancy is

dP‚Äã[ùíïP‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíïP‚Äã(ùíñ)]=‚àëk=0K‚àí1‚àëj=1Qk[œï^k,j‚Äã(ùíõ)‚àíœï^k,j‚Äã(ùíñ)sd^‚Äã(œï^k,j)]2.subscriptùëëùëÉsubscriptùíïùëÉùíõsubscriptùíïùëÉùíñsuperscriptsubscriptùëò0ùêæ1superscriptsubscriptùëó1subscriptùëÑùëòsuperscriptdelimited-[]subscript^italic-œïùëòùëóùíõsubscript^italic-œïùëòùëóùíñ^sdsubscript^italic-œïùëòùëó2d_{P}[\bm{t}_{P}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}_{P}(\bm{u})]=\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}\sum_{j=1}^{Q_{k}}\left[\frac{\hat{\phi}_{k,j}(\bm{z})-\hat{\phi}_{k,j}(\bm{u})}{\widehat{\mathrm{sd}}(\hat{\phi}_{k,j})}\right]^{2}.

The differences between observed and simulated œï^k,jsubscript^italic-œïùëòùëó\hat{\phi}_{k,j} are scaled by the prior predictive standard deviation of œï^k,jsubscript^italic-œïùëòùëó\hat{\phi}_{k,j}. We estimate sd‚Äã(œï^k,j)sdsubscript^italic-œïùëòùëó\mathrm{sd}(\hat{\phi}_{k,j}) from simulated observations from the prior predictive distribution.

The overall discrepancy is formed by taking the logarithm of the product of the two discrepancies dMsubscriptùëëùëÄd_{M} and dPsubscriptùëëùëÉd_{P}:

dT‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñ)]=log‚Å°{dM‚Äã[ùíïM‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíïM‚Äã(ùíñ)]‚ãÖdP‚Äã[ùíïP‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíïP‚Äã(ùíñ)]}.subscriptùëëùëáùíïùíõùíïùíñ‚ãÖsubscriptùëëùëÄsubscriptùíïùëÄùíõsubscriptùíïùëÄùíñsubscriptùëëùëÉsubscriptùíïùëÉùíõsubscriptùíïùëÉùíñd_{T}[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u})]=\log\left\{d_{M}[\bm{t}_{M}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}_{M}(\bm{u})]\cdot d_{P}[\bm{t}_{P}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}_{P}(\bm{u})]\right\}.

This formulation of dTsubscriptùëëùëád_{T} ensures that equal proportionate changes in dMsubscriptùëëùëÄd_{M} or dPsubscriptùëëùëÉd_{P} have the same additive effect on the overall discrepancy. Due to taking the logarithm, this discrepancy can be negative and its minimum is ‚àí‚àû-\infty, while the minimum of the strictly monotone transformation exp‚Å°{dT‚Äã[‚ãÖ,‚ãÖ]}subscriptùëëùëá‚ãÖ‚ãÖ\exp\{d_{T}[\cdot,\cdot]\} is 00. However, it is not necessary for the discrepancy function to be non-negative for the ABC algorithm to work properly (see Section¬†3.3). We only require the discrepancy function to induce an ordering of the simulated data with respect to the observed data.

The FP step establishes the formula for computing the discrepancies that is used in the ABC step. After the FP step, the actual ABC step is performed to obtain the approximate posterior model probabilities and posterior parameter distributions.

3.3 SMC ABC step

The specific ABC algorithm used for our application is the SMC ABC replenishment algorithm (Drovandi and Pettitt, 2011). This SMC ABC algorithm dynamically determines the non-increasing sequence of tolerances œµtsubscriptitalic-œµùë°\epsilon_{t}. In each iteration t=1,‚Ä¶,Tùë°1‚Ä¶ùëát=1,\ldots,T, the current particle set of size NùëÅN is ordered according to the discrepancies dT‚Äã[ùíï‚Äã(ùíõ),ùíï‚Äã(ùíñi)]subscriptùëëùëáùíïùíõùíïsuperscriptùíñùëñd_{T}[\bm{t}(\bm{z}),\bm{t}(\bm{u}^{i})] and is given by {œài=(ki,œïkii,ùíñi)}i=1Nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptùúìùëñsuperscriptùëòùëñsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñùëñsuperscriptùíñùëñùëñ1ùëÅ\{\psi^{i}=(k^{i},\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}^{i},\bm{u}^{i})\}_{i=1}^{N}. The procedure discards the NŒ¥=‚åàŒ¥‚ÄãN‚åâsubscriptùëÅùõøùõøùëÅN_{\delta}=\lceil\delta N\rceil particles with the highest discrepancies from the ordered particle set, so the particle subset Œ®={œài;i=1,‚Ä¶,N‚àíNŒ¥}\Psi=\{\psi^{i};\>i=1,\ldots,N-N_{\delta}\} contains the retained particles. The current tolerance level œµtsubscriptitalic-œµùë°\epsilon_{t} is lowered to the highest discrepancy value in the retained particle set, Œ®Œ®\Psi.

The other particles are resampled from the retained particles with replacement via multinomial resampling (Gordon et¬†al., 1993). For each j‚àà{N‚àíNŒ¥+1,‚Ä¶,N}ùëóùëÅsubscriptùëÅùõø1‚Ä¶ùëÅj\in\{N-N_{\delta}+1,\ldots,N\}, we set œàj=œà‚àósuperscriptùúìùëósuperscriptùúì\psi^{j}=\psi^{*}, where œà‚àósuperscriptùúì\psi^{*} is a random draw from the particle subset Œ®Œ®\Psi. In our case, all particles have equal weights, so Pr‚Å°(œà‚àó=œài)=1/(N‚àíNŒ¥)Prsuperscriptùúìsuperscriptùúìùëñ1ùëÅsubscriptùëÅùõø\Pr(\psi^{*}=\psi^{i})=1/(N-N_{\delta}) for i‚àà{1,‚Ä¶,N‚àíNŒ¥}ùëñ1‚Ä¶ùëÅsubscriptùëÅùõøi\in\{1,\ldots,N-N_{\delta}\}.

The resampling step introduces duplicated particles. To diversify the particle set, a reversible jump Markov chain Monte Carlo (RJ-MCMC) kernel is applied RtsubscriptùëÖùë°R_{t} times to each resampled particle. The invariant distribution of the RJ-MCMC kernel is the approximate posterior (3.1) with the tolerance level set to the current level œµtsubscriptitalic-œµùë°\epsilon_{t}. The number of RJ-MCMC steps, RtsubscriptùëÖùë°R_{t}, is set to a value such that the probability that a particle does not move during the RtsubscriptùëÖùë°R_{t} steps is approximately equal to a user-defined fixed small number cùëêc. Given cùëêc, RtsubscriptùëÖùë°R_{t} is estimated by

Rt=‚åàlog‚Å°(c)log‚Å°(1‚àípacc,t‚àí1)‚åâ,subscriptùëÖùë°ùëê1subscriptùëùaccùë°1\displaystyle R_{t}=\left\lceil\frac{\log(c)}{\log(1-p_{\mathrm{acc},t-1})}\right\rceil,

where pacc,t‚àí1subscriptùëùaccùë°1p_{\mathrm{acc},t-1} is the MCMC acceptance rate of the previous SMC iteration.

The RJ-MCMC proposal distribution for the model indicator is a discrete distribution denoted by qk,k‚àósubscriptùëûùëòsuperscriptùëòq_{k,k^{*}}, which gives the probability of proposing model k‚àósuperscriptùëòk^{*} given the current model kùëòk. In our application, we assume that all models have the same probability to be proposed irrespective of the current model. Given the proposed model, the proposal distributions for the parameters, denoted by qk‚Äã(œïk)subscriptùëûùëòsubscriptbold-italic-œïùëòq_{k}(\bm{\phi}_{k}), k=0,‚Ä¶,K‚àí1ùëò0‚Ä¶ùêæ1k=0,\ldots,K-1, are independent proposals, where the parameters of the proposal distributions are usually estimated from the current particle set. We employ multivariate normal independence proposal distributions, where the mean and variance-covariance matrix are estimated from the retained particle subset.

The algorithm stops when the overall acceptance rate in the RJ-MCMC steps drops below some minimum level or when the desired final tolerance level œµminsubscriptitalic-œµ\epsilon_{\min} is reached. The first condition is reasonable because the algorithm terminates when further moderate reductions of œµtsubscriptitalic-œµùë°\epsilon_{t} can only be achieved at excessive computational cost and are therefore not worthwhile given the computing resources.

The algorithm has two tuning parameters: the proportion of particles to be dropped at each SMC iteration, Œ¥ùõø\delta, and the desired probability of moving a particle during the sequence of RJ-MCMC move steps, 1‚àíc1ùëê1-c. The choice of these tuning parameters is generally considered to be problem-specific. Drovandi and Pettitt (2011) suggest values of 0.50.50.5 and 0.010.010.01 for Œ¥ùõø\delta and cùëêc, respectively, to be sensible general choices.

The initial particle set for the ABC SMC step is generated by a variant of the ABC rejection algorithm. A large number of particles {ki,œïkii,ùíñi}i=1N2superscriptsubscriptsuperscriptùëòùëñsuperscriptsubscriptbold-italic-œïsuperscriptùëòùëñùëñsuperscriptùíñùëñùëñ1subscriptùëÅ2\{k^{i},\bm{\phi}_{k^{i}}^{i},\bm{u}^{i}\}_{i=1}^{N_{2}} is simulated from the prior predictive distribution. From this set, the N‚â™N2much-less-thanùëÅsubscriptùëÅ2N\ll N_{2} particles with the smallest discrepancies form the initial particle set for the ABC SMC algorithm. The initial tolerance level œµ1subscriptitalic-œµ1\epsilon_{1} is the greatest discrepancy among the NùëÅN remaining particles.

A more detailed discussion of this ABC method is given in Lee et¬†al. (2015). A concise summary of the ABC algorithm for model selection and parameter estimation can be found in Appendix¬†A.

4 Application

4.1 Implementation details

There is an abundance of potential summary statistics available for ABC inference for models of spatial extremes. The advantage of using the FP step described in Section¬†3.2 is that the summary statistics that best explain a model or its parameters are weighted by the regression coefficients in the linear predictor as given by Equations¬†(3.2) and (3.3). Furthermore, superfluous summary statistics are eliminated through the backward stepwise procedure using the Akaike information criterion (AIC). The summary statistics ùíà‚Äã(‚ãÖ)ùíà‚ãÖ\bm{g}(\cdot) considered for our application are estimates of the pairwise F-madogram, the pairwise and tripletwise extremal coefficient, the pairwise Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau, and the composite score vectors for the five possible models, see Sections¬†2.3 and 2.4. To be consistent across all models, we also use the composite score statistics for the tùë°t copula models instead of the score statistics based on the full likelihood.

For the pairwise dependence indicators, the empirical estimates given in Section¬†2.3 are computed for all pairs of locations and binned into groups from small to large Euclidean distances. The means and standard deviations of the groups are used as regression summary statistics. For our application, we selected four approximately equal-sized groups.

A practical issue in computing the summary statistics for the tripletwise extremal coefficients is determining how similar one location triplet is to another among the (H3)binomialùêª3{H\choose 3} triplets, where HùêªH is the number of locations. Erhardt and Smith (2012) propose clustering the (H3)binomialùêª3{H\choose 3} triplets into Gùê∫G groups or clusters (with G‚â™(H3)much-less-thanùê∫binomialùêª3G\ll{H\choose 3}) based on the ordered pairwise location distances of the triplet‚Äôs three locations.

We used the kùëòk-median clustering algorithm via the function kcca from the R package flexclust (Leisch, 2006). For our particular application, we found that G=100ùê∫100G=100 groups suggested by Erhardt and Smith (2012) is too large. There was great similarity among the 100100100 clusters suggested by the algorithm and it was difficult to get reproducible cluster membership with 100100100 clusters. Instead, smaller values of Gùê∫G were tested and a Gùê∫G value of 101010 was chosen for our investigation. We take the mean and standard deviation for each group and add them to the vector ùíà‚Äã(‚ãÖ)ùíà‚ãÖ\bm{g}(\cdot) of regression summary statistics.

We selected the following independent priors for all models:

log‚Å°(Œª)ùúÜ\displaystyle\log\left(\lambda\right) ‚àºsimilar-to\displaystyle\sim ùí©‚Äã(1,‚Äâ4),ùí©14\displaystyle\mathcal{N}(1,\,4),
Œ∫ùúÖ\displaystyle\kappa ‚àºsimilar-to\displaystyle\sim ùí∞‚Äã(0,‚Äâ2),ùí∞02\displaystyle\mathcal{U}(0,\,2),
Œ±ùõº\displaystyle\alpha ‚àºsimilar-to\displaystyle\sim ùí∞‚Äã(0,œÄ/2),ùí∞0ùúã2\displaystyle\mathcal{U}(0,\,\pi/2),
log‚Å°(r)ùëü\displaystyle\log(r) ‚àºsimilar-to\displaystyle\sim ùí©‚Äã(0,‚Äâ8),ùí©08\displaystyle\mathcal{N}(0,\,8),
log‚Å°(ŒΩ)ùúà\displaystyle\log(\nu) ‚àºsimilar-to\displaystyle\sim ùí©‚Äã(0,‚Äâ1)‚Äã¬†truncated on¬†‚Äã[‚àí2.5,‚Äâ2.5].ùí©01¬†truncated on¬†2.52.5\displaystyle\mathcal{N}(0,\,1)\text{ truncated on }[-2.5,\,2.5].

These prior distributions put significant prior mass on regions of relevant posterior mass, see Figure¬†4 for the Brown-Resnick model. Furthermore, all the observed values of the dependence indicators are in regions of non-negligible prior predictive mass (see Appendix¬†E). Since we assume normal prior distributions for log‚Å°(Œª)ùúÜ\log(\lambda), log‚Å°(r)ùëü\log(r), and log‚Å°(ŒΩ)ùúà\log(\nu), we also used the log-transformations of these variables as the dependent variables in the FP step‚Äôs linear regressions. We did not transform Œ∫ùúÖ\kappa and Œ±ùõº\alpha.

For the FP step, 2,00020002,\!000 simulations were generated from the prior predictive distribution of each model to obtain the logistic and linear regression estimates. The SMC ABC replenishment algorithm was run with N=2,000ùëÅ2000N=2,\!000 particles and stopped when the particle acceptance probability in the RJ-MCMC steps was less than pacc,min=10‚àí2subscriptùëùaccsuperscript102p_{\mathrm{acc},\min}=10^{-2}. The SMC ABC tuning parameters were set to Œ¥=0.5ùõø0.5\delta=0.5 and c=0.01ùëê0.01c=0.01 as suggested by Drovandi and Pettitt (2011). In the initial ABC rejection step, N2=20,000subscriptùëÅ220000N_{2}=20,\!000 particles were simulated from the prior predictive distribution, of which the 10%percent1010\% with the smallest discrepancies to the observed data were selected to form the initial SMC ABC particle set.

It is straightforward to simulate from the tùë°t copula model because it only requires to obtain samples from a multivariate Student-tùë°t distribution and to apply the univariate Student-tùë°t CDF and the inverse unit Fr√©chet CDF to the margins. Simulating from most max-stable models is more difficult, since one realisation of the max-stable process is the pointwise maximum over infinitely many realisations of the spectral function (see Equation¬†(2.1)). For some max-stable models it is possible to obtain exact simulations by reordering the sampling of the spectral functions appropriately so that the simulation of spectral functions can stop in finite time after meeting a specific stopping rule (Schlather, 2002). However, for many models like the extremal-tùë°t or the Brown-Resnick model only approximate simulations are possible by applying the basic reordering idea. For an overview of simulation methods for max-stable processes, see Oesting et¬†al. (2015). Recently, exact simulation algorithms have been developed by investigating different representations. For example, Thibaud and Opitz (2015) present an algorithm for exact simulation of extremal-tùë°t processes and Dieker and Mikosch (2015) develop a method to obtain exact simulations from the Brown-Resnick process. Dombry et¬†al. (2016) introduce two general-purpose algorithms for the exact simulation of max-stable processes, which can be adapted to many max-stable models. For our application, we implemented their Algorithm¬†1 (simulation via extremal functions) for the extremal-tùë°t and the Brown-Resnick model. For our ABC application, which heavily depends on accurate simulations, we prefer to use exact simulation methods. However, exact simulation algorithms are in general computationally more expensive than approximate algorithms. For Algorithm¬†1 of Dombry et¬†al. (2016), on average HùêªH extremal functions need to be sampled to simulate one realisation of the max-stable process at HùêªH locations. On dense grids, this simulation method may therefore become too expensive and one has to resort to approximate algorithms. The advantage of Algorithm¬†1 of Dombry et¬†al. (2016) is that the expected number of simulated extremal functions does not depend on any parameters of the model. For example, for most of the other simulation methods the simulation effort of the extremal-tùë°t model increases strongly when ŒΩùúà\nu becomes large. Since simulation speed is crucial for ABC, we implemented the exact simulation routines in C++ using the Rcpp (Eddelbuettel and Fran√ßois, 2011) and RcppArmadillo (Eddelbuettel and Sanderson, 2014) interface to R.

4.2 South Australian annual maximum temperature data

South Australia experiences a dry and hot Mediterranean climate. Extreme high temperatures can cause public health and safety concerns, for example heatwaves and bushfires. Understanding the spatial distribution of maximum temperature around the state is a vital component in planning for future adverse events related to extreme high temperatures.

The data set considered in this paper contains annual maximum temperature values for the 181818-year-period spanning from 197919791979 to 199619961996 at 252525 weather stations around Adelaide, the capital of South Australia. The particular time period (1979‚àí1996)19791996(1979-1996) is the longest uninterrupted period of temperature recordings for the selected collection of weather stations reasonably close to Adelaide. The publicly available data were obtained from the Australian Bureau of Meteorology website. These maximum temperatures were originally recorded in monthly observation blocks and converted to yearly maximum temperature values. The autocorrelation plots of the yearly maxima for each observed location did not show any statistically significant temporal dependence in the data.

Figure¬†1 depicts the locations of the 252525 weather stations. Appendix¬†C provides detailed information on the marginal transformations of the data to the unit Fr√©chet scale. In addition, the assumption of unit Fr√©chet marginal distributions is checked for the transformed data set via QQ plots and Kolmogorov-Smirnov tests. The unit Fr√©chet assumption is not rejected at any location.

The analysis of the full data set showed that the station in Warooka on the peninsula is an outlier (see Appendix¬†H). There is almost no dependence between Warooka and the surrounding stations, which is not in accordance with any of our models. Therefore we discarded Warooka for the analyses presented in Sections¬†4.4 and 4.5. The results for the full data set can be found in Appendix¬†H.

4.3 Simulation study

We conducted a simulation study to assess the validity and effectiveness of our approach for the South Australian maximum temperature data set when it is assumed that one of the five models we consider is the true model. For each of the five models, we simulated 303030 data sets with the same pattern of locations and the same number of years as the original data set from the prior predictive distribution. Then we employed our ABC procedure (FP step, initial ABC rejection, SMC ABC step) to each simulated data set. To compute the composite score vector summaries, it is necessary to find the MCLEs for all the models for each simulated data set. The procedure for finding the MCLEs is outlined in Appendix¬†B.1. In 191919 cases there were numerical problems with the composite score vector summaries when evaluated at the MCLE for at least one of the models. In some cases the computation of the composite scores produced numerical errors, in other cases the composite scores were numerically 00 for all simulated observations and the standardisation failed. In all of these cases the procedure was aborted automatically. If this would happen for the real data set, one may spend more effort to find a value for the MCLE for which the composite score statistics can be computed. If that is not possible, the composite score statistics for the models causing the problems would have to be removed. In 31 cases, we terminated the SMC ABC algorithm before the acceptance rate fell below its stopping threshold. We incorporate the results of these data sets since the model probabilities typically do not change much over the course of the SMC iterations (see, e.g., Figure¬†3). Table¬†2 gives the frequencies of unsuccessful attempts and of premature terminations of the SMC ABC step for each of the models:

Row jùëój in the following matrix contains the average posterior probabilities for the different models (in the columns) across all data sets generated from model jùëój. The column order of the models is the same as the row order. The posterior model probabilities are estimated from the final SMC particle set.

{blockarray}‚Äãl‚Äãl‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äã&‚ÄãPr‚Å°(1|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(2|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(3|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(4|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(5|j)‚Äã{block}‚Äãl‚Äãl‚Äã[c‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc]‚Äãj=1‚Äã(extremal-t¬†WM)‚Äã0.370.320.150.090.07‚Äãj=2‚Äã(extremal-t¬†PE)‚Äã0.290.340.260.050.06‚Äãj=3‚Äã(Brown-Resnick)‚Äã0.160.180.580.040.05‚Äãj=4‚Äã(t¬†copula WM)‚Äã0.060.050.030.430.42‚Äãj=5‚Äã(t¬†copula PE)‚Äã0.020.010.020.460.49{blockarray}ùëôùëôùëêùëêùëêùëêùëê&Prconditional1ùëóPrconditional2ùëóPrconditional3ùëóPrconditional4ùëóPrconditional5ùëó{block}ùëôùëôdelimited-[]ùëêùëêùëêùëêùëêùëó1(extremal-t¬†WM)0.370.320.150.090.07ùëó2(extremal-t¬†PE)0.290.340.260.050.06ùëó3(Brown-Resnick)0.160.180.580.040.05ùëó4(t¬†copula WM)0.060.050.030.430.42ùëó5(t¬†copula PE)0.020.010.020.460.49\blockarray{llccccc}&\Pr(1|j)\Pr(2|j)\Pr(3|j)\Pr(4|j)\Pr(5|j)\\ \block{ll[ccccc]}j=1\text{(extremal-$t$ WM)}0.370.320.150.090.07\\ j=2\text{(extremal-$t$ PE)}0.290.340.260.050.06\\ j=3\text{(Brown-Resnick)}0.160.180.580.040.05\\ j=4\text{($t$ copula WM)}0.060.050.030.430.42\\ j=5\text{($t$ copula PE)}0.020.010.020.460.49\\

Moreover, Figure¬†2 shows boxplots of the distributions of the posterior model probabilities for simulated data sets from the different models.

The max-stable models and the tùë°t copula models are separated very well. The tùë°t copula models have low posterior probabilities for the max-stable data sets and vice versa. However, it is very hard to discriminate between the different correlation functions within the model classes. For example, when the true model is the tùë°t copula model with Whittle-Mat√©rn correlation function, the distributions of the posterior model probabilities are almost equal between the two tùë°t copula models (see Figure¬†2). In general, it is possible to discriminate between the Brown-Resnick model and the extremal-tùë°t models quite well. One notable exception is when the true model is the extremal-tùë°t model with powered exponential correlation function. In that case there is a high chance of a large posterior model probability of the Brown-Resnick model.

The misclassification matrix (see Lee et¬†al. (2015)) for the simulation study is provided in Appendix¬†B.2. Element (j,k)ùëóùëò(j,k) from the misclassification matrix contains the proportion of data sets from model jùëój that are classified as model kùëòk, where the classification rule is the highest posterior model probability. It is compared to the misclassification matrix obtained by applying the classical composite likelihood information criterion (Padoan et¬†al., 2010; Davison et¬†al., 2012).

4.4 Assessing quality of regression summary statistics obtained by FP step

In this section, we investigate the performance of the summary statistic set obtained by the FP step for the purpose of model selection for the South Australian maximum temperature data. The performance is summarised using the matrix of average posterior model probabilities. The (jùëój, kùëòk)-th element of this matrix corresponds to the average posterior probability of model kùëòk among all model jùëój simulations in the FP step‚Äôs training particle set. Given simulated data from model jùëój, the posterior model probabilities are estimated according to Equation¬†(3.2). The matrix is

{blockarray}‚Äãl‚Äãl‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äã&‚ÄãPr‚Å°(1|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(2|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(3|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(4|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(5|j)‚Äã{block}‚Äãl‚Äãl‚Äã[c‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc]‚Äãj=1‚Äã(extremal-t¬†WM)‚Äã0.360.330.160.090.06‚Äãj=2‚Äã(extremal-t¬†PE)‚Äã0.330.400.160.060.06‚Äãj=3‚Äã(Brown-Resnick)‚Äã0.160.150.560.070.06‚Äãj=4‚Äã(t¬†copula WM)‚Äã0.090.060.060.420.37‚Äãj=5‚Äã(t¬†copula PE)‚Äã0.060.060.060.370.46.{blockarray}ùëôùëôùëêùëêùëêùëêùëê&Prconditional1ùëóPrconditional2ùëóPrconditional3ùëóPrconditional4ùëóPrconditional5ùëó{block}ùëôùëôdelimited-[]ùëêùëêùëêùëêùëêùëó1(extremal-t¬†WM)0.360.330.160.090.06ùëó2(extremal-t¬†PE)0.330.400.160.060.06ùëó3(Brown-Resnick)0.160.150.560.070.06ùëó4(t¬†copula WM)0.090.060.060.420.37ùëó5(t¬†copula PE)0.060.060.060.370.46\blockarray{llccccc}&\Pr(1|j)\Pr(2|j)\Pr(3|j)\Pr(4|j)\Pr(5|j)\\ \block{ll[ccccc]}j=1\text{(extremal-$t$ WM)}0.360.330.160.090.06\\ j=2\text{(extremal-$t$ PE)}0.330.400.160.060.06\\ j=3\text{(Brown-Resnick)}0.160.150.560.070.06\\ j=4\text{($t$ copula WM)}0.090.060.060.420.37\\ j=5\text{($t$ copula PE)}0.060.060.060.370.46\\ .

This matrix is similar to the matrix obtained by the simulation study. Max-stable and tùë°t copula models are well separated. The estimated posterior model probabilities for models not belonging to the same model class (extremal-tùë°t, Brown-Resnick, tùë°t copula) are generally very low. However, it is difficult to identify the correct correlation function within each class.

In Appendix¬†D, the FP step‚Äôs matrix of average posterior probabilities is computed on a separately generated test particle set to check for overfitting. This matrix is almost identical to the one given in this section. The regression coefficients of the multinomial logistic regression for the model indicator are provided in Appendix¬†L.

4.5 Results for South Australian data

For the actual South Australian data without the station in Warooka, Figure¬†3 shows the progression of the proportions of particles pertaining to the different models across the SMC iterations. Simultaneous 95%percent9595\% intervals for these model probability estimates were obtained from the fact that the model indicator is a multinomial variable (Sison and Glaz, 1995).

The preferred model is the Brown-Resnick model. In the final particle set after the last SMC iteration, about 63%percent6363\% of the particles are from the Brown-Resnick model. From the remaining particles, 26%percent2626\% belong to one of the two tùë°t copula models and 11%percent1111\% belong to one of the two extremal-tùë°t models. The model probabilities keep fairly constant over the course of the SMC iterations. The posterior probabilities of the tùë°t copula models slightly increase over time at the expense of the other models.

The estimated approximate marginal posterior distributions for the parameters of the best-fitting Brown-Resnick model are provided in Figure¬†4 and Table¬†3. For all parameters, we get posteriors that are unimodal and more informative than the respective prior distributions. Parameter estimation results for the other models are provided in Appendix¬†F.

In Appendix¬†G, the pairwise extremal coefficient functions evaluated at the median posterior parameter values are plotted for all the models.

To check the overall goodness of fit, we compare the observed pairwise F-madogram and Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau estimates with their posterior predictive distributions. To that end, we simulated 10,0001000010,\!000 data sets from the posterior predictive distribution. Each data set (18 observations on each of 25 locations) was generated by drawing one particle with replacement from the final particle set and then simulating the data set depending on the selected particle‚Äôs model indicator and parameter values. Given this sample, we can estimate the posterior predictive distributions of all the dependence indicators for all the location pairs. Note that the final particle set contains particles from all models with an estimated posterior probability greater than 00, so the posterior predictive distributions are the Bayesian model averages over all models.

In Figure¬†5, we compare the observed pairwise F-madogram (left plots) and Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau (right plots) estimates to their posterior predictive distributions. Only one location pair falls outside the 95%percent9595\% posterior predictive probability interval for the F-madogram. This location pair is depicted in the left bottom plot of Figure¬†5.

Despite excluding Warooka, our models are not able to perfectly capture the dependence structure. For high distances, the posterior predictive distribution puts too much mass on summary values that indicate high dependency, for smaller distances it puts too much mass on summary values indicating low dependency, see also the boundaries of the 95%percent9595\% posterior predictive probability intervals in Figure¬†5. Due to the geography of the locations, especially the vicinity of most stations to the ocean, more complex dependence structures would have to be considered to achieve a better fit.

5 Discussion

The research presented in this paper expands the use of ABC for spatial extremes applications to include model selection problems. We show that the spatial dependence structure of the maximum temperature data collected around the state of South Australia is best captured by a Brown-Resnick model out of a collection of three max-stable models and two non-extremal Student-tùë°t copula models. For this analysis, we exclude the station in Warooka because we consider it to be an outlier. It should be emphasised that this paper provides a case study of the application of ABC to model selection problems for spatial extremes and is not meant to be directly used to inform decision-making. The models we consider are not able to capture the intricacies of the particular environmental process in their entirety.

We would like to highlight some extensions to the straightforward geometrically anisotropic max-stable models used that would provide a more realistic representation of the spatial structure of the maximum temperature for further research. Our work has ignored any effect that might be attributable to the fact that part of the region in Figure¬†1 is actually a large body of water that would affect the local temperature near the coast. As such, it might be more appropriate to focus on the land mass of the region. One might determine a transformation of the land mass to a regular geometry while keeping the distance measure positive-definite by using complex spatial smoothers (Wood et¬†al., 2008; Sangalli et¬†al., 2013). Blanchet and Davison (2011) discuss several options to model anisotropic behaviour beyond geometric anisotropy.

All the models we consider assume unit Fr√©chet marginal distributions. If that is not the case, one has to transform the data properly prior to model fitting, as we did, or the number of parameters to be estimated has to be increased drastically by three GEV parameters per location. Therefore, the marginal GEV parameters are often modelled themselves by employing spatial smoothing models. This kind of modelling is required if the fitted max-stable model is used to interpolate the measurements at unobserved locations on the original measurement scale. Erhardt and Smith (2012) interpolate the GEV parameters on unobserved locations by applying Kriging. The R package SpatialExtremes (Ribatet et¬†al., 2017) facilitates the use of P-splines for GEV response surface modelling. The shape parameter Œæùúâ\xi often exhibits little variability and follows no discernible pattern and is therefore set to a constant value over the whole space (Ribatet, 2013; Erhardt and Smith, 2012). Investigations of the appropriate modelling of the marginal GEV parameters and quantification of the corresponding uncertainty on model results are beyond the scope of this study but would be of interest in further work. There are also other models for spatial extremes that could be considered, such as those based on latent variable models (Davison et¬†al., 2012).

In addition, there are still numerous improvement opportunities for the ABC model selection algorithm and ABC algorithms in general. Use of more sophisticated classification methods such as random forests (Pudlo et¬†al., 2016) in the FP step could potentially provide improved performance at the expense of increased computation and less straightforward interpretations of the classification method‚Äôs direct outputs. Optimising the efficiency of the ABC algorithm is also an active research area. Such optimisations are particularly vital for applications involving computationally heavy model simulations such as the exact simulation of max-stable models on a dense grid. Methods such as Lazy ABC (Prangle, 2016) and expectation propagation ABC (Barthelm√© et¬†al., 2015) introduce additional approximations to the standard ABC method to decrease the computational time required to obtain the approximate posterior for computationally expensive models. As noted in Barthelm√© et¬†al. (2015), these methods appear promising for model selection problems as well.

Appendix A ABC algorithm summary

In the following summary of our ABC method, we have omitted the time indices for the particles and the parameter proposal distributions qk‚Äã(‚ãÖ)subscriptùëûùëò‚ãÖq_{k}(\cdot) to avoid notational clutter. The two steps of our ABC method for model selection and parameter estimation are:

Appendix B Additional remarks and results for simulation study

B.1 Procedure to find maximum composite likelihood estimates (MCLEs)

The MCLEs were found through numerical optimisation of the pairwise log-likelihood. For some data sets and models, the result of the optimisation procedure heavily depended on the starting value. Therefore, for each data set and model we ran the optimisation routine repeatedly using random starting values from the prior distribution until we had five runs where the optimisation converged. Then we used the result from the run which led to the highest value of the objective function. For the Student-tùë°t copula models, we used the MLEs found for the full log-likelihood as starting values for optimising the pairwise log-likelihood. We employed the box-constrained Broyden, Fletcher, Goldfarb, and Shanno (BFGS) quasi-Newton optimisation method, see Byrd et¬†al. (1995).

B.2 Misclassification matrices for simulation study

B.2.1 Misclassification matrix obtained by ABC procedure

Element (j,k)ùëóùëò(j,k) in the misclassification matrix below gives the probability that a data set generated from model jùëój in the simulation study is classified as being from model kùëòk, where the classification rule is the highest posterior model probability estimated from the final SMC particle set:

{blockarray}‚Äãl‚Äãl‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äã&‚ÄãPr‚Å°(1|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(2|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(3|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(4|j)‚ÄãPr‚Å°(5|j)‚Äã{block}‚Äãl‚Äãl‚Äã[c‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc‚Äãc]‚Äãj=1‚Äã(extremal-t¬†WM)‚Äã0.380.280.210.070.07‚Äãj=2‚Äã(extremal-t¬†PE)‚Äã0.170.380.420.040.04‚Äãj=3‚Äã(Brown-Resnick)‚Äã0.040.000.960.000.00‚Äãj=4‚Äã(t¬†copula WM)‚Äã0.040.040.040.440.44‚Äãj=5‚Äã(t¬†copula PE)‚Äã0.000.000.000.520.48.{blockarray}ùëôùëôùëêùëêùëêùëêùëê&Prconditional1ùëóPrconditional2ùëóPrconditional3ùëóPrconditional4ùëóPrconditional5ùëó{block}ùëôùëôdelimited-[]ùëêùëêùëêùëêùëêùëó1(extremal-t¬†WM)0.380.280.210.070.07ùëó2(extremal-t¬†PE)0.170.380.420.040.04ùëó3(Brown-Resnick)0.040.000.960.000.00ùëó4(t¬†copula WM)0.040.040.040.440.44ùëó5(t¬†copula PE)0.000.000.000.520.48\blockarray{llccccc}&\Pr(1|j)\Pr(2|j)\Pr(3|j)\Pr(4|j)\Pr(5|j)\\ \block{ll[ccccc]}j=1\text{(extremal-$t$ WM)}0.380.280.210.070.07\\ j=2\text{(extremal-$t$ PE)}0.170.380.420.040.04\\ j=3\text{(Brown-Resnick)}0.040.000.960.000.00\\ j=4\text{($t$ copula WM)}0.040.040.040.440.44\\ j=5\text{($t$ copula PE)}0.000.000.000.520.48\\ .

B.2.2 Misclassification matrix obtained by CLIC

We compare the misclassification matrix for our simulated data sets obtained by our ABC procedure to the misclassification matrix obtained by classifying the simulated data sets according to the composite likelihood information criterion (CLIC), see, e.g., Davison et¬†al. (2012) and Padoan et¬†al. (2010). This is the classical criterion traditionally used for model selection of max-stable models, for which only a composite likelihood representation is available. It is a generalisation of the Akaike information criterion and accounts for the model misspecification due to using the composite likelihood.

The CLIC is defined as

CLIC=‚àí2‚Äãp‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï~M‚ÄãC‚ÄãL‚ÄãE;ùíõ)+2‚Äãtr‚Äã(ùë±^‚ÄãùëØ^‚àí1),CLIC2ùëù‚Ñìsubscript~bold-italic-œïùëÄùê∂ùêøùê∏ùíõ2tr^ùë±superscript^ùëØ1\mathrm{CLIC}=-2\,p\ell(\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{MCLE};\bm{z})+2\,\mathrm{tr}\left(\hat{\bm{J}}\hat{\bm{H}}^{-1}\right),

where p‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï~M‚ÄãC‚ÄãL‚ÄãE;ùíõ)ùëù‚Ñìsubscript~bold-italic-œïùëÄùê∂ùêøùê∏ùíõp\ell(\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{MCLE};\bm{z}) is the pairwise/composite log-likelihood (Equation¬†(2.5)) evaluated at the maximum composite likelihood estimate (MCLE), ùë±^^ùë±\hat{\bm{J}} is an estimate of ùë±‚Äã(œï~M‚ÄãC‚ÄãL‚ÄãE)=Var‚Äã[‚àáœïp‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï~M‚ÄãC‚ÄãL‚ÄãE;ùíõ)]ùë±subscript~bold-italic-œïùëÄùê∂ùêøùê∏Vardelimited-[]subscript‚àábold-italic-œïùëù‚Ñìsubscript~bold-italic-œïùëÄùê∂ùêøùê∏ùíõ\bm{J}(\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{MCLE})=\mathrm{Var}\left[\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}\>p\ell(\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{MCLE};\bm{z})\right], and ùëØ^^ùëØ\hat{\bm{H}} is an estimate of ùëØ‚Äã(œï~M‚ÄãC‚ÄãL‚ÄãE)=‚àíE‚Äã[‚àáœï2p‚Äã‚Ñì‚Äã(œï~M‚ÄãC‚ÄãL‚ÄãE;ùíõ)]ùëØsubscript~bold-italic-œïùëÄùê∂ùêøùê∏Edelimited-[]subscriptsuperscript‚àá2bold-italic-œïùëù‚Ñìsubscript~bold-italic-œïùëÄùê∂ùêøùê∏ùíõ\bm{H}(\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{MCLE})=-\mathrm{E}\left[\nabla^{2}_{\bm{\phi}}\>p\ell(\tilde{\bm{\phi}}_{MCLE};\bm{z})\right]. We estimate ùë±ùë±\bm{J} and ùëØùëØ\bm{H} as suggested in Ribatet (2013, p.¬†163).

In order to be able to compare all models on equal terms, we also computed the CLIC for the Student-tùë°t copula models based on their pairwise likelihood representation.

Using the CLIC as classification criterion, the misclassification matrix for the simulated data sets is

The inversion of ùëØ^^ùëØ\hat{\bm{H}} failed sometimes. For a given data set, all models for which the inversion failed were disregarded. To assess the magnitude of the bias and the loss of information incurred by this approach, it is counted for how many models it was not possible to invert ùëØ^^ùëØ\hat{\bm{H}} for each simulated data set. The table of counts across all data sets is given below:

# models where inversion failed 0 1 2 3 4 5
# simulated data sets 95 29 11 13 1 1

The aim of this section is to provide a rough comparison between the misclassification matrices of the ABC and the classical approach. We consider the quality of our CLIC-based estimate of the misclassification matrix to be sufficiently accurate for our purpose. Otherwise a more elaborate estimation technique for the CLIC would have to be employed.

This may lead to overfitting. There are only minimal changes to the matrix reported in Section¬†4.4.

Appendix E Prior predictive checks

To gauge whether the models and prior choices are appropriate for the South Australian data (when excluding Warooka), we compare the observed F-madogram and Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau estimates for all pairs of locations with their prior predictive distributions. Figure¬†9 is equivalent to Figure¬†5, replacing draws from the posterior predictive distribution with draws from the prior predictive distribution. One draw from the prior predictive distribution is generated by choosing one of the five models with equal probability, then simulating one draw from each of the parameter priors of the chosen model (for the prior specifications see Section¬†4.1), and then simulating one data set from the chosen model given the parameter draws.

Figure¬†9 shows the observed F-madogram (left) and Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau (right) estimates for all location pairs vs.¬†their prior predictive means and the 95%percent9595\% prior predictive probability intervals. The prior predictive distribution serves its purpose as a preliminary model for the observed data. The 95%percent9595\% prior probability intervals are very wide and cover all the observed values, so the prior predictive distribution is sufficiently general and not too informative. Compared to the true data, the prior predictive distribution more strongly favours dependence indicators signalling low dependency.

Appendix F Posterior distributions

Figures¬†10, 11, 12, and 13 show the posterior distributions of the parameters of the extremal-tùë°t models with the Whittle-Mat√©rn and powered exponential correlation function and the Student-tùë°t copula models with the Whittle-Mat√©rn and powered exponential correlation function, respectively, when the station in Warooka is excluded. These models do not have very high posterior model probabilities. For example, the estimated posterior model probability of the extremal-tùë°t model with Whittle-Mat√©rn correlation function is 3.4%percent3.43.4\% (67 out of 2000 particles) after the final SMC ABC iteration. Since this is a rather small sample size, the Monte Carlo error of the reported posterior estimates is high. If preciser estimates of the posterior distributions are desired for any of these models, one can run the sequential Monte Carlo ABC algorithm (or any other ABC algorithm) once more exclusively for the particular model of interest with the focus solely on parameter estimation.

Appendix G Extremal coefficient function plots

A common graphical goodness-of-fit check of spatial max-stable models is to visually assess how well the theoretical pairwise extremal coefficient curve as a function of the distance between the locations fits the cloud of observed pairwise extremal coefficients. Since for our models the distances depend on the parameters governing the geometric anisotropy, we have to assume a specific parameter configuration to compute the interpoint distances for all the points in the cloud. Different anisotropy parameters give rise to different clouds of observed extremal coefficients. For each model, we will set the parameter values to their respective posterior median values.

Specifically, we compute the distance between locations ùíô1subscriptùíô1\bm{x}_{1} and ùíô2subscriptùíô2\bm{x}_{2} as

h‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2)=‚Äñùë®~‚Äã(ùíô1‚àíùíô2)‚ÄñŒª~,‚Ñésubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2norm~ùë®subscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2~ùúÜh(\bm{x}_{1},\bm{x}_{2})=\frac{\|\tilde{\bm{A}}(\bm{x}_{1}-\bm{x}_{2})\|}{\tilde{\lambda}},

where the anisotropy matrix is

ùë®~=(1001/r~)‚ãÖ(cos‚Å°Œ±~sin‚Å°Œ±~‚àísin‚Å°Œ±~cos‚Å°Œ±~),~ùë®‚ãÖmatrix1001~ùëümatrix~ùõº~ùõº~ùõº~ùõº\tilde{\bm{A}}=\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\ 0&1/\tilde{r}\end{pmatrix}\cdot\begin{pmatrix}\cos\tilde{\alpha}&\sin\tilde{\alpha}\\ -\sin\tilde{\alpha}&\cos\tilde{\alpha}\end{pmatrix},

and Œª~~ùúÜ\tilde{\lambda}, Œ±~~ùõº\tilde{\alpha}, and r~~ùëü\tilde{r} are the posterior medians of the range, rotation angle, and principal axes ratio parameters, respectively. That is, we transform the location space to ùí≥~=(ùë®~/Œª~)‚Äãùí≥~ùí≥~ùë®~ùúÜùí≥\tilde{\mathcal{X}}=\left(\tilde{\bm{A}}/\tilde{\lambda}\right)\mathcal{X} and compute the Euclidean distances in this transformed space.

For these transformed distances h‚Ñéh, the theoretical extremal coefficient curve of the Brown-Resnick model with power variogram evaluated at the posterior median of the smoothness parameter, Œ∫~~ùúÖ\tilde{\kappa}, is given by (Davison et¬†al., 2012)

Œ∏‚Äã(h;Œ∫~)=2‚ÄãŒ¶‚Äã{a‚Äã(h;Œ∫~)/2},ùúÉ‚Ñé~ùúÖ2Œ¶ùëé‚Ñé~ùúÖ2\theta(h;\tilde{\kappa})=2\,\Phi\left\{a(h;\tilde{\kappa})/2\right\},

where Œ¶‚Äã{‚ãÖ}Œ¶‚ãÖ\Phi\{\cdot\} is the CDF of the standard normal distribution and

a‚Äã(h;Œ∫~)=2‚ÄãhŒ∫~.ùëé‚Ñé~ùúÖ2superscript‚Ñé~ùúÖa(h;\tilde{\kappa})=\sqrt{2h^{\tilde{\kappa}}}.

For the extremal-tùë°t model, we have (Davison et¬†al., 2012)

Œ∏‚Äã(h;ŒΩ~,Œ∫~)=2‚ÄãT1;ŒΩ~+1‚Äã{(ŒΩ~+1)‚Äã1‚àíœÅ‚Äã(h;Œ∫~)1+œÅ‚Äã(h;Œ∫~)},ùúÉ‚Ñé~ùúà~ùúÖ2subscriptùëá1~ùúà1~ùúà11ùúå‚Ñé~ùúÖ1ùúå‚Ñé~ùúÖ\theta(h;\tilde{\nu},\tilde{\kappa})=2\,T_{1;\tilde{\nu}+1}\left\{\sqrt{(\tilde{\nu}+1)\>\frac{1-\rho(h;\tilde{\kappa})}{1+\rho(h;\tilde{\kappa})}}\right\},

where T1;ŒΩ~+1‚Äã{‚ãÖ}subscriptùëá1~ùúà1‚ãÖT_{1;\tilde{\nu}+1}\{\cdot\} denotes the central Student-tùë°t CDF with ŒΩ~+1~ùúà1\tilde{\nu}+1 degrees of freedom, œÅ‚Äã(h;Œ∫~)ùúå‚Ñé~ùúÖ\rho(h;\tilde{\kappa}) is one of the correlation functions described in Appendix¬†K, ŒΩ~~ùúà\tilde{\nu} is the posterior median of the degrees of freedom parameter, and Œ∫~~ùúÖ\tilde{\kappa} is the posterior median of the smoothness parameter.

As discussed in Section¬†2.3, the extremal coefficient is not defined for the Student-tùë°t copula models. We can nevertheless use Equation¬†(2.4) to generate meaningful summary statistics measuring dependence. However, no theoretical extremal coefficient curve is available and the functional form of the underlying coefficient to which the estimates converge is unknown. Therefore, we have to estimate the underlying coefficient for a given set of parameters Œ∫~~ùúÖ\tilde{\kappa} and ŒΩ~~ùúà\tilde{\nu} at any distance h‚Ñéh. For a given distance h‚Ñéh, we obtain the estimate by computing Equation¬†(2.4) for a sample of size 500,000500000500,\!000 generated from a bivariate tùë°t copula model with distance h‚Ñéh. To allow for a concise description of the results, we denote the underlying coefficient to which the estimates converge by extremal coefficient in accordance with the max-stable models.

Figure¬†14 shows the extremal coefficient function plots for all models when the station in Warooka is excluded, one plot for each model. The extremal-tùë°t models fail to capture the extremal coefficients at low and medium distances, where most of the points are concentrated. The Brown-Resnick model, on the other hand, does not capture the extremal coefficients at large distances very well, but it provides the best fit for small and medium distances. The tùë°t copula models also provide an adequate fit.

Appendix H Analysis when including Warooka station

In this section, we present the results of our ABC analysis when the station in Warooka is included.

The progression of estimated posterior model probabilities is depicted in Figure¬†15. By including Warooka, the estimated posterior model probabilities change significantly. When Warooka is included, the posterior model probability of the Brown-Resnick model is 40%percent4040\% at the final SMC iteration. When Warooka is excluded, this probability is 63%percent6363\%. On the other hand, the posterior model probabilities of the tùë°t copula models rise to 33%percent3333\% (powered exponential correlation function) and 20%percent2020\% (Whittle-Mat√©rn correlation function), so the tùë°t copula models have a higher combined posterior model probability than the Brown-Resnick model. The posterior model probabilities of the extremal-tùë°t models remain low.

The marginal posterior distributions for the two most probable models are depicted in Figure¬†16 (Brown-Resnick model) and Figure¬†17 (tùë°t copula model with powered exponential correlation function). They are mostly similar to the posterior distributions when Warooka is excluded (cf.¬†Figures¬†4 and 13). However, the posterior distributions for the principal axes ratio, /, put more mass on very high values. (Note that the densities of the logarithms are plotted.) The posterior distributions for the rotation angle are more concentrated on the upper half. On the other hand, the posterior distribution for the tùë°t copula model‚Äôs degrees of freedom parameter ŒΩùúà\nu is slightly shifted to the left.

The extremal coefficient function plots are displayed in Figure¬†18. The pattern is similar to Figure¬†14.

Figure¬†19 shows the posterior predictive analysis for the pairwise F-madogram and Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau estimates when Warooka is included. For 8%percent88\%/7%percent77\% of the location pairs, the observed F-madogram/ Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau estimate falls outside the 95%percent9595\% posterior predictive probability interval. The bottom plots in Figure¬†19 connect the locations in these pairs with lines. All of the outlying location pairs have an unusually low observed mutual dependency and Warooka on the peninsula is included in all of them but one. Therefore, we consider the observations collected at Warooka as being outlying observations according to our models.

Appendix I Derivations of bivariate log-likelihoods

For all max-stable process models, the bivariate cumulative distribution function (CDF) is equal to

F‚Äã(z1,z2)=exp‚Å°{‚àíV‚Äã(z1,z2)},ùêπsubscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2ùëâsubscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2F(z_{1},z_{2})=\exp\left\{-V(z_{1},z_{2})\right\},

where V‚Äã(z1,z2)ùëâsubscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2V(z_{1},z_{2}) is called the exponent measure (see Davison et¬†al. (2012)). We obtain

f‚Äã(z1,z2)=exp‚Å°{‚àíV‚Äã(z1,z2)}‚Äã[V1‚Äã(z1,z2)‚ãÖV2‚Äã(z1,z2)‚àíV1,2‚Äã(z1,z2)],ùëìsubscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2ùëâsubscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2delimited-[]‚ãÖsubscriptùëâ1subscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2subscriptùëâ2subscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2subscriptùëâ12subscriptùëß1subscriptùëß2f(z_{1},z_{2})=\exp\left\{-V(z_{1},z_{2})\right\}\left[V_{1}(z_{1},z_{2})\cdot V_{2}(z_{1},z_{2})-V_{1,2}(z_{1},z_{2})\right],

and so the log-likelihood is

I.1 Brown-Resnick model

The bivariate CDF of the Brown-Resnick model with power variogram has the form (Ribatet, 2013)

K.2 Powered exponential

The powered exponential (also called ‚Äústable‚Äù) correlation function reads (Davison et¬†al., 2012)

œÅ{h(ùíô1,ùíô2;Œª,Œ±,)/,Œ∫}=exp(‚àíhŒ∫),\rho\{h(\bm{x}_{1},\bm{x}_{2};\lambda,\alpha,)/,\kappa\}=\exp\left(-h^{\kappa}\right),

where Œ∫ùúÖ\kappa is a smoothing parameter with 0<Œ∫‚â§20ùúÖ20<\kappa\leq 2.

Its partial derivatives w.r.t.¬†œïi=Œªsubscriptitalic-œïùëñùúÜ\phi_{i}=\lambda, œïi=Œ±subscriptitalic-œïùëñùõº\phi_{i}=\alpha or œïi=subscriptitalic-œïùëñabsent\phi_{i}=/are

‚àÇœÅ‚àÇœïi=‚àíexp‚Å°(‚àíhŒ∫)‚ÄãŒ∫‚ÄãhŒ∫‚àí1‚Äã‚àÇh‚àÇœïi=‚àíœÅ‚ÄãŒ∫‚ÄãhŒ∫‚àí1‚Äã‚àÇh‚àÇœïiùúåsubscriptitalic-œïùëñsuperscript‚ÑéùúÖùúÖsuperscript‚ÑéùúÖ1‚Ñésubscriptitalic-œïùëñùúåùúÖsuperscript‚ÑéùúÖ1‚Ñésubscriptitalic-œïùëñ\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial\phi_{i}}=-\exp\left(-h^{\kappa}\right)\kappa h^{\kappa-1}\frac{\partial h}{\partial\phi_{i}}=-\rho\,\kappa h^{\kappa-1}\frac{\partial h}{\partial\phi_{i}}

and the partial derivative w.r.t.¬†Œ∫ùúÖ\kappa is

‚àÇœÅ‚àÇŒ∫=‚àíexp‚Å°(‚àíhŒ∫)‚ÄãhŒ∫‚Äãlog‚Å°(h)=‚àíœÅ‚ÄãhŒ∫‚Äãlog‚Å°(h).ùúåùúÖsuperscript‚ÑéùúÖsuperscript‚ÑéùúÖ‚Ñéùúåsuperscript‚ÑéùúÖ‚Ñé\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial\kappa}=-\exp\left(-h^{\kappa}\right)h^{\kappa}\log(h)=-\rho\,h^{\kappa}\log(h).

For the Brown-Resnick model with power variogram, a‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2;œï)ùëésubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2bold-italic-œïa(\bm{x}_{1},\bm{x}_{2};\bm{\phi}) is given by

a‚Äã(ùíô1,ùíô2;œï)=2‚ÄãhŒ∫,ùëésubscriptùíô1subscriptùíô2bold-italic-œï2superscript‚ÑéùúÖa(\bm{x}_{1},\bm{x}_{2};\bm{\phi})=\sqrt{2\,h^{\kappa}},

Appendix L Multinomial logistic regression coefficients obtained by FP step

Table¬†LABEL:table:log_reg_coefs contains the estimated multinomial logistic regression coefficients for model choice from the FP step. All covariates were standardised before running the regressions. Empty cells in Table¬†LABEL:table:log_reg_coefs belong to coefficients which have been excluded by the backward stepwise procedure.

For the pairwise dependence indicators (F-madogram, extremal coefficient, Kendall‚Äôs œÑùúè\tau), the location pairs were grouped according to their Euclidean distance and then the average and the standard deviation of the indicator were computed for each group. The four groups were:

Group Distance interval
1 (0,1]01(0,1]
2 (1,2]12(1,2]
3 (2,3]23(2,3]
4 (3,6]36(3,6]

For details on the procedure for clustering the location triplets into ten clusters, see Section¬†4.1.

After the backward stepwise procedure most covariates are included in the multinomial logistic regression model. The composite score statistics between the two extremal-tùë°t models are clearly substitutes. This exemplifies that it is very hard to distinguish between the different correlation functions within the same class of models.
